<HEAD>Berkshire County's Last Diaper Service To Fold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The diaper business has hit bottom, forcing the last remaining diaper service in <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to call it quits. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Holzer </PERSON>, vice president of <LOCATION> Aladco </LOCATION>, said that with more parents using disposable diapers his customers have dropped from 400 a decade ago to a mere 60 scattered across the county. `` We ca n't operate at that low a volume,'' he said Tuesday. <PERSON> Holzer </PERSON> said he had hoped negative publicity about disposable diapers choking landfills would slow the trend, but that did n't happen Toward the end, he found that he could n't even give away his business. People declined, even when diaper service was offered as a gift, <PERSON> Holzer </PERSON> said. And so, in May, the Adams company, which also operates a laundry, dry cleaning and linen and uniform rental business, is dropping its diaper division.
