 Sex Aid. Keep a little tin box by the bed, and donate 25 pence every time, uh, you know, whenever you do. Wink wink, nudge nudge. The campaign announced by <ORGANIZATION> Marie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stopes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a charity which supports family planning in the Third World, sounds like a publicity stunt. It is a publicity stunt. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hindmarsh </PERSON>, fund-raising manager for the charity, said Wednesday that it has been working away quietly for 20 years, `` talking earnestly to people _ and it has n't done the trick.'' `` We now realize that we need more hype like Band Aid and Comic Relief to draw people's attention to the problem, so we are asking people to make love and save the world.'' At the suggested rate of 25 pence -LRB- 43 cents -RRB-, Ms. <PERSON> Hindmarsh </PERSON> said the average British couple could give 12.50 pounds -LRB- about $ 21.25 -RRB- a year. `` They can save it up or write us a check every six months or put it in a little tin by the bed,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hindmarsh </PERSON> said. `` We do n't really care how they do it,'' she confessed. `` At the end of the day we just want their money.'' There is a serious point too: `` I think it will help people focus on the fact that they have the freedom to make love without producing another mouth to feed,'' she said.
