<HEAD>Lebanese Huddle In Bunkers During Shelling Duels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The murderous bombardment in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the worst in four years, has squeezed people's daily lives to four hours of scurrying about their business and 20 hours underground. When Syrian and Christian artillery gunners rest at daybreak, thousands of trapped residents cautiously emerge from bunkers. Their first order of business is to hurriedly buy fresh supplies of food, water, candles, gas lamps, decks of cards and sleeping pills. Just before the antagonists resume the deadly duel that began three weeks ago, they rush back to shelters on both sides of the Green Line that divides the city into Moslem and Christian sectors. Most nightclubs, bars, restaurants, cafes and movie houses are closed. So are schools and universities. Banks operate haphazardly for two or three hours a day, depending on the ferocity of the shelling. `` The only thing that matters nowadays is self-preservation,'' said <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Trad </PERSON>, a pharmacist in <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ashrafiyeh </LOCATION> district. `` Survival is the name of the game.'' He did not recall a similar stampede for sleeping pills in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year civil war. `` I do n't have statistics. But if this continues, we will soon run out of tranquilizers,'' said Trad, whose pharmacy is shielded by tall sandbag walls. There are no severe shortages at present. Wholesalers try to monopolize goods in order to raise prices, and stores order new stock during lulls in the fighting. Some residents manage to joke about the shelling. `` Tell my friends in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> not to worry about me,'' said <PERSON> Bahjat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON>, a police reporter who lives in east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Maameltein suburb Like many others, he commuted between <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s two sectors before the latest round of fighting `` I have all the fireworks. Some 200 shells explode around my apartment nightly. The house is always shaking like a swing, and I am swinging,'' quipped <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON>, 55. A Greek Catholic bachelor, <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> does not use the basement shelter of his seaside apartment building because his 92-year-old mother can hardly move. `` I simply ca n't leave her alone.'' When a missile detonated a large gas storage tank at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port, winds blew the flame and smoke in the direction of his house, 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` I'm lik a roasted chicken,'' he joked to friends on the telephone. The fighting pits army commander Gen. Mily Christian units against an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse Moslem militiamen. It was touched off by an air-and-sea blockade <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> clamped on militia-run illegal ports on March 6 in a bid to reinstate government authority. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> heads a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> in the fractured nation's dual government. The Syrians and <LOCATION> Mosmilitia </LOCATION> allies, who recognize the rival Moslem Cbinet of former Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, retaliated by sealis to the Christian enclave and blockading its 1 million inhabitts with their bato the sea. Ensuing bouts of savage bombardment have blown hundreds of houses, wrecked power plants, destroyed city water pipes and threatened to crush the nation's infrstructure. Police statistics show an average of 3,000 shells fell on the city and its environs every day of the past three weeks, killing more than 150 people and wounding 500. Mor than 90 have been killed and 300 wounded in easnd the adjoining Christian hinterland. The other casulaties were in the city's Moslem sector and Druse-controlled hills. <PERSON> Nabil </PERSON> <PERSON> Haddad </PERSON>, 38, a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> grcer, said he has been surviving with his wife aong with 40 neighbors in the candle-lit basement of their 6-story apartment building. `` I death so close. I give up,'' he said at the doorstep of their shelter in east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s poor <LOCATION> Einrict </LOCATION>. `` We're suffocating. I do n't think we're e.'' <PERSON> Haddad </PERSON> opens his store only during morning lulls in shelling. <PERSON> Shukri </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahhoud </PERSON>, a banker who lives posh, hilltop <LOCATION> Rabieh </LOCATION> district on east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s northern flank, was more optimistic. `` We ` to make it,'' he `` I do n't think the world is going to al the annihilation of 1 million Christians. Thisng to stop.'' <PERSON> Lahhoud </PERSON> said he and his neighbors while away the hours in running games of poker and backgamloor underground shelter, which houses a power generator. The city's Moslem sector is virtually a ghost town. Tens of thousands of residents have fled to relative safety in east and south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Those who stayed behind also spend nights in shelters as soldiers with multibarreled mobile rocket launchers roam around, firing off a barrage, then moving quickly before retaliatory fire comes. Civilians take the punishment. `` It's a dirty trick but no one dares protest it,'' ident who requested anonymity.
