<HEAD>Cigarette Smoking Boosts Metabolism, Burns 100 Calories a Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Smoking makes the body burn more calories, according to a study that helps explain one of life's biological injustices: why people put on weight when they give up cigarettes. The research publi care of about 100 calories a day for the typical smoker. Smokers typically weigh five to 10 pounds less than non-smokers, and they usually put on that much weight when they break the habit. The question has been why this happens. Part of the reason is that folks often eat more when they stop smoking, and some studies have shown they are more likely to crave sugar. While preliminary evidence suggested that they also burned calories more slowly, many experts thought this effect was small. In the past, scientists have studied this by watching changes in metabolism when people smoke while sitting still. In the lastest work, researchers decided to see what happened to metabolism when people smoked while moving around, just as they do in real lifeought it was conceivable we would n't see any effect,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, who directed the <ORGANIZATION> Universityrgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> study that's published in the New England Journal of Medicine. `` To our surprise, whe opposite, that it was much more enhanced. It reversed our thinking. The implication is that the metabolic eing -RRB- is much more important than everyone else has considered.' When staying ng increases metabolism by about 5 percent. But it raises it by about 12 percent. Among other things, this could help explain hy some people balloon when they quit cigaretteothers manage to hold their weight steady. `` If people tenn coffee breaks or while relaxing at home watching TV, they wo n't gain as much weight'' when they quit, said <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>. `` Those who smoke while active are likely to be thinnero begin with because of their smoking.'' So they risk putting on more when they stop smoking.. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigotti </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> noted that some people, especiall keep smoking because they are afraid of gaining weight. `` Until our cultural obsession wih slenderness abates,'' she wrote, `` we must pay more attention to the way weight gain impedes efforts to stop smoking if we are to continue the progress of the past quarter century toward a smoke-free society.'' Exprts note that while obesity is dangerous, smokers should not leof gaining weight keep them from quitting. `` Your health risk is immeasurably improved whestop smoking, no matter how much weight you gain,'' said <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>. He also pointed out that people can offset their newly slowed metabolisttle extra exercise. `` All you would need to do is walk about a mile extra er that,'' <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said. `` That' hard as it sounds.''
