<FIRST>r w PM-PollClosings     04-06 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll Closings,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uniform Poll Closing Time Clears House by Broad Margin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polling places across the nation would close at a uniform time in presidential elections under a plan on its way to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> after winning House approval. The bill, approved 238-154 on Wednesday, is designed to reduce the effect of outcome projections made hours before the polls close in the Wet and in some late-closing states elsewhere. `` The importance of Western votes for president is being diminished just because of where we live,'' Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., declared The measure has passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> twice before only to languish in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but lawmakers say <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> prospects are better this year. The bill calls for closing times of 9 p.m. EST, 8 p.m. CST and 7 p.m. MST. In presidential election years only, the switch from daylight-saving time to standard time in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> time zone would be postponed a maximum of two weeks. Polls there would close at 7 p.m. PDT. Under the timetable, polling places would shut their doors simultaneously, making it impossible for results from some states to indicate a winner and influence turnout elsewhere. Only presidential years would be covered by the bill, which would take effect in 1992 and would not apply to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The plan is designed to dovetail with a 1985 agreement under which major television networks said they would voluntarily refrain from projecting election results within a state until the polls close there. It is unclear if local races are actually affected by early projections. House Rules Committee Chairman <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., however, said Tuesday that he believed the phenomenon may have contributed to the 1980 defeat of Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Ullman </PERSON>, D-Ore., then chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> Either way, lawmakers say voter frustration because of such projections is basically unhealthy. `` It's unfair to either party that the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> would announce the final result of an election to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> before the final votes are counted,'' Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Tenn </LOCATION>., told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> The only critic of the bill to take the floor, Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>., described it as `` a <PERSON> Rube </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> device that will louse up the states, cause them a great deal of confusion and travail. He said it actually could reduce turnout by shortening voting hours on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and possibly prompting <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states to open the polls at later hours than they do now. Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, D-Wash., the measure's sponsor, said studies have shown an earlier poll closing will prompt voters to vote earlier and thus the fear of a drop in turnout `` is simply not substantiated by the facts. The extension of daylight-saving time in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> zone would take place only in presidential election years. It would last for a maximum of two weeks and apply to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> as well as the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> panhandle but not the rest of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
