<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s insistence on cutting the capital gains tax is a `` thorn in our negotiations'' as <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and congressional bargainers try to complete a budget agreement. `` I think we're confused,'' Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., said Wednesday night, after a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> `` We're a room of good intentions,'' he said, but, `` there's a difficult thorn in our negotiations and that's capital gains.'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> have been meeting with key members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to craft a plan for meeting the goal of a $ 100 billion deficit in fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. About $ 28 billion in either new revenues or spending restraint would be needed to meet that goal, according to White House estimates. As part of the deficit reduction plan in his fiscal 1990 budget, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed cutting the tax rate on capital gains to 15 percent, about in half. The president contends the rate cut would raise about $ 4.8 billion in revenue. However, congressional estimates show the reduction would be a big revenue loser in the long run and, Democrats contend, the rich would benefit the most from the tax break. Although his own budget included several billion dollars in tax increases and new user fees, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> contends those did not violate his campaign pledge against any new taxes. With Democrats opposing the capital gains scheme, coming up with a deficit-reduction plan has proven difficult since alternative tax revenues or more spending cuts would be needed. Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, has proposed in the talks that half the deficit reduction, about $ 14 billion, come from revenues _ a combination of taxes, sales of government assets, and new user fees <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s revenue proposals produced about the same amount, but included the claimed capital gains influx He said Wednesday that resolution of the tax issue is crucial to the success of the talks. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said he was not discouraged, but it would be difficult. `` We're going to continue to talk ... but I do n't know that we're going to meet any of the deadlines,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has an April 15 deadline for completing the budget. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> declined to comment on the specifics of the meeting. `` It's just part of the budget process,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. Asked if he had brought something new to discuss, he said, `` I did n't bring a thing.''
