<HEAD>US Analysts Disappointed by Gorbachev Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s call for an end to the `` export of revolution and counterrevolution'' to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> disappointed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> analysts who were hoping for a stronger sign that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> would curtail its military aid to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials, pursuing a more conciliatory Central American policy than President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, agreed with congressional leaders last month not to seek military aid for the Contra guerrillas of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. They hoped that in response, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would curtail the estimated $ 6 billion in aid the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> sends to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, the $ 1 billion in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc assistance to leftist guerrillas in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` While his words about not exporting revolution are welcome, they are not matched by deeds which would give his words credence,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, meeting in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, scolded Western media for reporting a Cuban-Soviet rift and gave no indication that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> would be cutting its aid to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island, estimated at about $ 6 billion a year. `` As in the past, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> have a common approach to the key problems of international affairs,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` The most imme