hange those policies quickly,'' said <PERSON> Wiarda </PERSON>. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> applauded <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s statement on the export of revolution, while at the same time criticizing <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s past policies. `` I hope <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> follows <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s advice,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION> `` Certainly, much of our trouble in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> comes from <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> activities. If they can be closed down, this will help peace to come to that troubled region.'' A former Cuban diplomat now living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> `` expectations were too high for this meeting.'' `` I think there is definitely conflict between <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, but that it will take some time'' to become public, said <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON>, who worked in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> before defecting in 1980. <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON> has seen hints that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will reduce aid to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> as well as pressure <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> to curtail military interference in other countries, but does n't think the trend will become obvious until both countries enter their next five-year economic period in 1991. `` Since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power, the Soviets have been asking the Cubans to fulfill their annual trade agreements. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has had problems, for example, filling his sugar quota. He has not been doing it,'' he said. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, who opposes the type of political reforms <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is pressing in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that no such changes are needed in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. `` But if Soviet aid was reduced, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> would face a political crisis,'' said <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader, who has developed strong ties to the Soviet military and intelligence agencies over the decades, may be biding his time, hoping that conservatives in those organizations will force <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> from power, said <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> is betting on the opposition,'' said <PERSON> Benemelis </PERSON>.
