<HEAD>Malaysian Legislature Enacts Law Against Eating Turtle Eggs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an anti-extinction effort, a state legislature has enacted a law under which anyone caught with the eggs of leatherback turtles can be fined up to $ 363 or sentenced to six months in jail. Many Malaysians eat the eggs as a delicacy, believing they increase sexual prowess. The law passed Wednesday by the <LOCATION> Trengganu </LOCATION> state assembly in <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Trengganu </LOCATION>, 180 miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur, says the only lawful purpose for keeping the eggs is for hatching by the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngah </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he proposed the law because the number of leatherback turtles laying eggs in Rantau <PERSON> Abang </PERSON>, near <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Trengganu </LOCATION>, had declined to about 500 in recent years and measures were needed to prevent their extinction. The turtles, measuring as much as five feet in diameter and weighing up to 900 pounds, range the seas as far as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> but return to the beaches of Rantau <PERSON> Abang </PERSON> each June to August to lay their eggs. Scientists say the turtles, which live as long as 100 years, return each year to the exact beach where they were born to lay up to 70 eggs.
