<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Psychologists are consulting with nationally recognized experts on disasters and tragedies to help residents young and old cope with the nation's worst oil spill. `` The stress down there in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> is incredible,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` People need to be aware the stress is going to be affecting them. They need to be aware that their stress is going to impact on their children.'' A 24-hour toll-free telephone line staffed by mental health professionals to take calls from the distressed is being set up, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> set up a similar line for its employees in the aftermath of the space shuttle Challenger disaster. Among the most common feelings are hopelessness, helplessness and worthlessness, he said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> has been consulting with <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a psychologist at the Univerity of <LOCATION> Maryland-Baltimore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> known to police, fire and medical services around the country as the founder of a process known as critical incident stress debriefing. The process is designed to relieve the stress emergency service personnel encounter in mass-casualty incidents and other crises. A variation of the process may be valuable to the Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> communities devastated by the spill, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> has done similar work in other afflicted communities, like <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, after a gunman shot up a shopping mall, killing six people and wounding 10. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> warned that the children in the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> area would be among the first to show the stress. `` He said do n't be surprised if children ask for cooking oil to put in the bathtub, or out in the mud puddle,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> psychologist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gist </PERSON>, a leading disaster expert, was scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> today, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, state coordinator of emergency services. `` Mental health -LRB- professionals -RRB- should plan on seeing problems ... for two to three years at least,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` Probably longer because of the total loss of lifestyle that may occur. The loss of lifestyle is as important as loss of income.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> suggested to <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> that the effects on employment be evaluated as quickly as possible. `` Those that will lose their livelihood for the next year or two will need vocational rehablitation, or it soon will have a negative impact on their mental health,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. In the interim, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said, the emphasis will be on education, trying to describe the reactions that are normal in such a situation and offering ways to deal with them.
