<HEAD>Najib Declares Truce; Kabul Attack Kills 10; Pakistanis Sentenced
For Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government declared a cease-fire in its war against the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas for <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>, the Islamic holy month of fasting. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said the unilateral cease-fire would begin at midnight today. If the rebels refused to observe the sanctity of the fasting month, he said, government troops would retaliate. It was at least the fourth cease-fire declared by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> since January 1987. The first truce was disregarded by both sides, and the guerrillas ignored all subsequent calls. The latest cease-fire was broadcast Wednesday by the official <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier, guerrilla rockets slammed into downtown Kqabul, killing six people and wounding 23, a government official said on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> Radio said 10 people were killed and 39 wounded. On Tuesday, at least six people were killed and eight wounded by rockets that hit residential neighborhoods. Meanwhile, a special security court convicted two Pakistanis of spying. Sgt. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashraf </PERSON> was sentenced Wednesday to 18 years imprisonment and Cpl. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Afzal </PERSON> was sentenced to 16 years. <PERSON> Ashraf </PERSON>, 35, and <PERSON> Afzal </PERSON>, 25, confessed to spying for Pakistani intelligence agencies. Judge <PERSON> Obaid </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakhi </PERSON> said they could have been sentenced to death but he and the other two judges hearing the case had acceded to their requests for leniency. <PERSON> Sakhi </PERSON> said the sentences could be appealed. <PERSON> Ashraf </PERSON> and <PERSON> Afzal </PERSON> said they worked for Pakistani intelligence agencies and were `` forcibly sent'' to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by their superior officers. <PERSON> Ashraf </PERSON> said he received a $ 1,000 bonus, while <PERSON> Afzal </PERSON> sai