<HEAD>Honduras Approves New U.S. Military Training Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers have agreed to let <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces continue joint training exercises with Honduran troops in this Central American country that borders <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. In a separate action, the legislature also approved new measures for cooperating with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to fight drug trafficking. The military exercises agreement was approved by a 132-2 vote on Wednesday. The lawmakers who voted no said the measure could hurt regional peace efforts. The two countries have engaged in more than 80 joint military training exercises involving at least 60,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and 20,000 Honduran troops during the past 38 years. The exercises were stepped up in 1982 when relations between <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and the leftist Sandinista government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> deteriorated and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> built an air base in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> also has served as a refuge, training ground and staging base for Nicaraguan rebels, about 11,000 of whom have lived with their families in camps near the Nicaraguan border since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government cut off military aid to them in February 1988. An estimated 1,100 American troops currently are stationed at the <ORGANIZATION> Enrique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cano </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, about 50 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. The base is considered among the most important centers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military operations in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has been supporting the government of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in its nine-year war against leftist rebels. Under the drug agreement, Honduran officials said they will work with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to crack down on drug production and trafficking. Both nations are to share information and human and technological resources. During the past six years, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast has become a transfer point for drug shipments from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the most-publicized local case, reputed drug baron <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> returned home to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> in 1986 after escaping from a Colombian prison. His arrest in April 1988 at his home in <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION> and rapid deportation to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> touched off riots. Extradition of Hondurans is prohibited by the constitution. <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> remains jailed at the federal prison in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, serving a three-year sentence for escaping from a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> prison in 1971.
