<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index plunged today, ending seven days of gains, while the dollar rose substantially against the Japanese yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose 48.54 points to a record high on Wednesday, shed 365.01 points, or 1.1 percent, to finish trading at 32,995.78. It was the index's second-largest decline this year, following a 366.21-point drop on March 20, when it finished at 31,654.80. Stocks fell almost across the board as participants expressed concern about the recent rapid rise in the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index, which had gained more than 1,800 points since last Tuesday, said a dealer with a major securities firm in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Uncertainty over possible political instability caused by a widening stock-profiteering scandal also discouraged participants, the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` The scandal has been continuing for some time, but speculators are very concerned now about the situation,'' he said. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, whose party is under fire for its links to <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the information services conglomerate at the center of the scandal, suffered a major blow Wednesday with reports he had received $ 380,000 from the firm at fund-raising parties in May 1987. In the scandal, the company reportedly sold hundreds of thousands of unlisted shares of a real-estate subsidiary at discount prices to about 150 influential public and business figures. The recipients of the shares made substantial profits after over-the-counter trading began and the stocks quickly rose in value. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s public support ratings have plunged to about 10 percent and he now faces strong pressure from the political opposition to resign. `` Investors' second-largest concern is inflation, which made them either step off to the sidelines or sell issues because of the upcoming release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate,'' the dealer said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate for March is to be announced Friday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Inflation and subsequent interest rate hikes to slow the economy could discourage stock investment. Trading was active, with volume on the first section estimated at 1.1 billion shares, down from Wednesday's 1.8 billion shares. On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 132.15 yen, up 0.78 yen from Wednesday's 131.37-yen finish. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency started trading at 131.93 yen and ranged between 131.75 and 132.25 yen. A trader with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said the dollar-yen exchange rate changed little during the day as investors stayed on the sidelines trying to avoid major moves ahead of the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate. `` Basically, the market has more demand for the dollar than the yen, mainly because of the higher interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said the trader, speaking on condition of anonymity. For currency investors, higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates make the dollar more attractive than the yen.
