<HEAD>Black Leaders Say They Will Hold Daley to `Open Door' Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor-elect <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s promise that the doors of his office would remain open to blacks was greeted with guarded optimism by many of the political leaders who lost control of City Hall. The promise highlighted <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s Tuesday night victory speech. A day later, acting Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> told reporters, `` You heard him say it. We'll make sure he sticks to it.'' Also helping hold <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> to his word, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> said, is the practical matter of having to face re-election in 1991. `` I'm sure he'll be extremely careful. They've got a short time. You've got to have continuity in government. You ca n't just go in there and clean out all the blacks,'' said <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who is black. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s victory over chief rival <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, the lone black in Tuesday's election, earned him the right to complete the final two years of the late <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>'s second term. And <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> invoked the memory of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as well as his political boss-father, the late <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, in promising that `` The City That Works'' will work first to unite an electorate deeply divided along racial lines. `` The openness and fairness that the late Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> talked about will be in my administration in the city of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, whose victory ended six years of black political control in the nation's third-largest city. `` A mayor today has to bring people together from one end of this city to the other,'' he added, `` to accomplish the things that are necessary to give people a good quality of life.'' During a round of interviews, the 46-year-old <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said he planned to leave soon for a brief vacation and would make few moves until his transition team completed its report. His inauguration is set for April 24 _ his 47th birthday. But before rushing off to attend to business that has stacked up in his state's attorney's office during the four-month campaign, he proposed several programs reminiscent of the shirt-sleeve professionalism that earned <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, in his father's days, the moniker of `` The City That Works.'' `` I will bring out the best of my father _ he knew city government,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said. `` He knew state and federal government. He loved this city and worked very hard for this city and I'll try to be like him.'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>' most prominent supporter, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, called for party unity and for blacks to move beyond the rivalry between <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. `` The basic <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> coalition has remained a bit too divided and when we unite we will win,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, pointing out, `` there are only 18 months before the next election.'' Unofficial totals showed <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> finishing with 55 percent of the vote, to 43 percent for <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and 3 percent for Republican <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON>. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was helped to victory Tuesday by overwhelming white support, low black turnout, and clear majorities among liberal, lakefront voters and Hispanics.
