<HEAD>Twaiwan To Send Official Delegation To China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> will send an official delegation to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for the first time to attend the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> next month, the government announced today. The government said the 12-member delegation will be led by Finance Minister <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> and will include officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and government-owned banks. The decision, taken by the government Cabinet at a regular weekly meeting, was regarded as another step in a new Nationalist inititive to counter Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s efforts to isolate <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> internationally. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu-chu </PERSON>, told reporters the Cabinet's decision did not signal a change in government policies toward <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> would continue to oppose official contacts with the rival communists who won a civil war in 1949, forcing the Nationalists to flee to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> said the delegation would not discuss relations between the rival governments and that the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> decided to approve the trip because the annual meeting was being organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and not <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. He said the delegation would attend the three-day meeting, which begins on May 4, to ensure that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> could `` actively participate'' in the development bank and also to fulfill <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s obligations as a founding member of the bank <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung-tung </PERSON>, history professor at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, described the government's decision as `` a major breakthrough'' and said it could lead to further flexibility toward the mainland. He said it was probably intended to pressure the Chinese communists to accept de facto Nationalist rule over this island. The Nationalists continue to claim they are the legitimate government of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and have maintained a policy of no contacts, no talks, no compromise toward communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since their defeat on the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> mainland. But in the past year, the Nationalists have relaxed their policy on private contacts between Taiwanese and mainland Chinese and have allowed an exchange of visits, trade and cultural ties. The <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was founded in 1966 to help regional development. The 47-member organization voted in 1986 to admit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and changed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s membership name from the <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ the official <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> name _ to <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Nationalist officials protested then, saying the change relegated <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to a provincial government under <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Nationalists boycotted the development bank's annual meetings in 1986 and 1987 but attended last year's meeting in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, where the bank has its headquarters. <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> said the Nationalists are still opposed to the <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> designation. He said the Nationalists would continue to negotiate with the bank to work out a compromise solution acceptable to both parties. Since the 1970s, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has been virtually isolated diplomatically. It is now recognized by only 23 nations, while most other countries recognize the mainland government.
