<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> told a state commission investigating charges of patronage in city hiring that some apparently improper procedures amounted to `` peanuts'' when compared to the city's overall hiring system. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> appeared Wednesday before a commission studying claims that the <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, a clearinghouse for city job applicants, was used to award city jobs to politically connected people. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Integrity </ORGANIZATION> has heard testimony that the <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> had become a patronage operation, contrary to <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s intent. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said the commission's hearings had created the impression `` that there is massive patronage in my administration and that this massive patronage was hidden behind a ` sham' affirmative action program.'' `` These charges are false,'' he said. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> called the number of <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> jobs filled under questionable circumstances from 1983 to 1986 `` peanuts.'' The Talent Bank placed about 3,000 people in jobs, most paying less than $ 20,000 a year. `` If I had wanted to have a massive patronage program, I could have,'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said. `` But I did not want to have, nor did I have, a patronage operation.'' In his defense, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said testimony had described practices at the Talent Bank that he would not have approved. Those practices involved only a part of the <ORGANIZATION> Talent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s job referral services _ the laborers, deck hands and ferry agents at two agencies, he said. `` And the T