<HEAD>Protests Continue In Korea After Crackdown On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with protests, Roh meeting. No pickup.
^By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers and radical students demonstrated for the seventh straight day today to protest the police assault that broke a strike at <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s largest shipyard. At least 12 people were reported arrested. Government officials said the unrest in <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION> was becoming a showdown between authorities and `` labor movement forces,'' and President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> met with security officials to discuss the protest. `` The most urgent task facing us now is to safeguard the nation's free democratic system from leftist forces,'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> told the meeting at the presidential residence in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION>, 150 miles southwest of the capital, hundreds of striking workers hurled rocks and firebombs at police in the streets around the strike-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> shipyard, news reports said. Police responded with tear gas, they said. The news reports said 2,000 striking workers demonstrated. In the last two days, about 200 police, workers and citizens were injured in the street battles, the news agency <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> said. It said a house and 38 cars were burned by firebombs thrown by striking workers. Protests broke out after police raided the shipyard March 30, arresting 700 workers and ending a strike that had left 400 people injured since Dec. 12. Most of those arrested were released, but formal charges have been filed against 10 union leaders. About 3,000 police guarded the shipyard. Company officials said 60 percent of the shipyard's 19,500 employees reported to work. Police today arrested about a dozen strikers who attacked non-striking workers on their way to work, <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> said. Hundreds of police were deployed around residential areas to protect non-striking workers, it said. `` The government's authority is being tested, and we will not back down,'' said a senior government official in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The three main opposition parties dispatched investigative teams to <LOCATION> Ulsan </LOCATION> today to look into the situation. Before departure, they urged the government to stop using forceful means and try to settle the problem through dialogue. Prosecutor-general <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gi-chun </PERSON> today called for stern measures to stop violent protests and said the government was prepared for a `` major showdown'' with leftist groups. On Wednesday, the government ordered an investigatation of 25 leading dissident and labor groups which have either sought contact with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for talks on national unification or spearheaded anti-government rallies.
