<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of thousands of city dwellers seeking to escape from a record heat wave found the beaches too hot to handle. Even Death Valley had cooler readings. `` It's hotter than sin,'' said <LOCATION> Seal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> lifeguard <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON>. `` People are even jumping into the showers with their clothes on out here.'' And forecasters said there's more heat ahead. Wednesday's 105 degrees at the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> surpassed by a whopping 15 degrees the record of 90 for April 5, set in 1971. It was the hottest reading ever posted in April, breaking the 100-degree mark set April 23, 1910, and tied on Tuesday. Forecasters said today's predicted high of 102 degrees downtown will easily eclipse the record 91-degree peak set April 6, 1939. The spring heat wave was spawned by a high-pressure system expected to linger over the West for several more days, said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecaster <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. More than 250,000 people fled to the beach Wednesday seeking relief from the spell of arid weather, but mercury levels topping 100 degrees wilted the throng of cool-seekers on the sun-roasted sands. It was cooler in the desert, but not by much. The mercury hit 103 in <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and 104 in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>. The suburban community of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> registered the nation's highest temperature, with a sizzling 109 degrees Electricity consumption _ 14,282 megawatts at 4 p.m. Wednesday _ was the highest ever for an April day, but still shy of the peak 15,987 megawatts used on Sept. 6, 1988, when the temperature downtown was 110 degrees, said <PERSON>