No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas today ignored a cease-fire declared by the government and fired missiles and rockets at <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and three other cities, witnesses and the government said. A missile blew up a fuel truck parked near a petroleum tank depot on the northern edge of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Several trucks parked nearby also exploded. A cloud of black smoke, visible over the city of 2 million, drifted from the site. There was no immediate word on casualties. An Afghan truck driver who said he was part of a convoy hauling fuel down the <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> Highway from <LOCATION> Hayratan </LOCATION>, on the Soviet border, said guerrillas tried to hijack some of the trucks a few miles north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The driver, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the hijackers got about a mile before they were attacked by two government helicopters. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said guerrillas fired rockets and cannons at the cities of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sarobi </LOCATION>. Ministry spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said government troops held their fire. He had no information on casualties. His report could not be confirmed. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s military command announced a unilateral cease-fire Wednesday night on the eve of <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>, the Islamic holy month. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that the government would retaliate with renewed force if the U.S.-backed guerrillas broke the cease-fire. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said guerrillas fired 32 rockets and cannon rounds today at the southern city of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>, where government forces have been besieged for the past year. Fewer than 100 rounds were fired at <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, he said. In the past two weeks, the government has accused the guerrillas of firing as many as 12,000 rounds a day at the city, which is 75 miles east of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said he had no indication how many rounds were fired at <LOCATION> Sarobi </LOCATION>, midway between <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>. The Ramadan cease-fire was at least the fifth unilateral cessation of hostilities declared by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> since January 1987. None has succeeded. The guerrillas have ignored every government-declared cease-fire, and the government itself usually quickly follows suit. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, who left <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Monday, still was waiting for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visa in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He wants to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to hold a special <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> session on the Afghan fighting. On Wednesday, guerrilla rockets slammed into downtown <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, killing six people and wounding 23, a government official said on condition of anonymity. Official Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said 10 people were killed and 39 wounded. Most of the Afghan guerrillas are based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. They have received support from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and other countries in their decade-old war against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s protege government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> ended its nine-year involvement in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> Feb. 15, but <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is still supplying the <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> government. Wednesday's rockets spewed shrapnel and debris as they hit a small park next to the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> Hotel and a commercial district several blocks away. The rockets, which landed four to 10 blocks from the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, were fired before noon, when sidewalks and marketplaces are crowded with pedestrians.
