<HEAD>State Fined For Prison Overcrowding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today fined the state $ 164,250 for prison overcrowding and ordered that the money be used to set up a bail fund for indigent defendants. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> ruled the state was in contempt of court for failing to limit to 250 the number of prisoners awaiting trial in an intake unit. Overcrowding at <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s only jail for inmates awaiting trial has been a problem for years, but mushroomed last year after the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> passed laws allowing drug defendants to be held without bail. The <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, under pressure from <LOCATION> Pettine </LOCATION>, opened two annexes to the intake unit, but has been unable to keep up with the exploding population. Construction of a new prison building has been stalled by local opposition in <LOCATION> Cranston </LOCATION>, where the Adult Correctional Institutions complex is located. Last fall, <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> gave the state until Feb. 20 to reduce the population at the intake unit to 250. As of Monday, the population was 464, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiNitto </PERSON>, state <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> imposed fines of $ 50 per extra inmate per day from Feb. 20 to March 13, and said further fines up to $ 289,000 or more would be imposed if necessary to meet his order to reduce crowding. `` I think that's just what was needed to ensure this problem is taken care of,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, executive director of the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> sued the state 13 years ago over prison conditions. <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> ordered the state to turn over the money within 15 days to the Corrections Department, but stayed the order to give state officials a chance to appeal. <PERSON> DiNitto </PERSON> said he had not yet seen the ruling and would not comment on it. The governor said the decision will be appealed. <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> praised the state for submitting long-range plans to alleviate overcrowding, but said the state should be fined because it ignored options such as the bail fund proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>. Any prisoner being held on $ 5,000 or less cash bail will be eligible to have bail paid by the fund. <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> recommended that maximum use be squeezed from the money by bailing first those prisoners being held on $ 1,000 bail or less before those being held on higher amounts. `` These pre-trial detainees are in jail only because they are too poor to make bail,'' <PERSON> Pettine </PERSON> wrote.
