<HEAD>Navajo Police Chief Ordered from Reservation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT TO Kellogg, sted Kellog; Picks
up 6th graf, `In other ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Navajo tribal judge has banned the tribe's police chief from the reservation for failing to enforce court orders related to embattled Chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>'s struggle to retain power Window Rock District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazzie </PERSON> signed an order Wednesday excluding Police Chief <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> from the reservation pending a hearing on Monday. An anti-MacDonald majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has voted to place <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> on leave, but the flamboyant head of the nation's largest <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> tribe has resisted `` For the last two months, I've just been a football back and forth between the two factions,'' said <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, who remained at his office late Wednesday. <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> was found in contempt and fined $ 500 by the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> earlier this week for having failed to enforce a court order barring <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowman </PERSON>, an appointee of the pro-MacDonald <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, from taking over <PERSON> Yazzie </PERSON>'s court. In other developments Wednesday: _ Tribal Controller <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, confronted by 50 angry <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> appointees and others, handed over 31 paychecks that had been withheld by order of the anti-MacDonald majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ The general manager of tribal radio station <ORGANIZATION> KTNN </ORGANIZATION> said the tribal attorney general's office told him in a memorandum that <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, because of a temporary restraining order issued by tribal court, should not be allowed to use the station's air time to make the weekly `` Chairman's Report. <ORGANIZATION> KTNN </ORGANIZATION> General Manager <PERSON> Freddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the station would have to disobey because of concerns about fairness, free speech and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> requirements. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the station would not drop either <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>'s report or one made by <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskie </PERSON>, the interim chairman selected by the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` This borders on trying to censor somebody,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` It's just like telling a newspaper what to print or what not to print.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> also said, `` I ca n't allow politics to jeopardize our good standing with the FCC. The issue is n't MacDonald or <PERSON> Haskie </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON> was placed on paid administrative leave by the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> after witnesses before a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee testified he received gifts and kickbacks in connection with tribal business dealings. <PERSON> MacDonald </PERSON>, who has denied such wrongdoing, has maintained the council's action was invalid and illegal. He has tried to retain his authority by firing opponents and those who attempt to remain neutral.
