<HEAD>Leningrad Officials Bemoan Election Rout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> blamed psychological attacks and malicious press coverage for the humiliating defeat of 12 city officials in last month's elections, a newspaper reported Thursday. But others at a special meeting called to discuss the election disaster said the party itself was responsible for the `` crisis of confidence'' in its abilities, said <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION>, the Russian republic's official party and government newspaper. The meeting, the first extraordinary session of the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party organization in 30 years, came four days after some party members demanded the resignation of the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> leadership, the newspaper said. Leningraders on March 26 rejected every one of local officials running for seats in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s new parliament, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyev </PERSON>, a candidate member of the party's ruling Politburo and regional party chief, ran unopposed and still lost because more than half the voters crossed out his name on the ballot. He characterized the results as `` depressing,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossia </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday's meeting `` occurred in an atmosphere of openness, honesty and toughness of evaluation, and impartial criticism, which we have dreamed about since the beginning of perestroika.'' The newspaper concluded that if such a meeting had occurred previously, the party might not have suffered so in the elections. `` Leningraders are not satisfied with the tempo and path of perestroika in the city,'' the newspaper quoted V.P. <PERSON> Smirnov </PERSON> as saying. `` They do n't feel that the leadership of the city defends the interests of the population, of the working class or the intelligentsia,'' said <PERSON> Smirnov </PERSON>, a radio controller and member of the regional party leadership. Clearly, `` a crisis of confidence has been outlined,'' he said. But the newspaper said many speakers blamed the loss on `` malicious press, strongly creating a negative stereotype of the party bureaucrats.'' It listed four party leaders who `` spoke with alarm about the psychological attack being carried out against the party. And is n't it strange that some organs of the press united with forces which are extremely far from the ideas of Marxism-Leninism. The report did not give examples of what they regarded as `` malicious'' press coverage. `` We insufficiently evaluated the ideological prejudice and bourgeois illusions which have been spreadly recently, and the dissatisfaction of the people with the growth of the deficit, inflation, crime, miscalculations in the organization of the cooperative movement,'' the newspaper said, paraphrasing the four officials. It identified the four as Y.A. <PERSON> Petrosyan </PERSON>, the director of an institute; Y.A. <PERSON> Sidorenko </PERSON>, an official of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>; S.B. <PERSON> Petrov </PERSON>, director of a sewing factory; and V.A. <PERSON> Yefimov </PERSON>, party leader of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> region. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said the turning point of the meeting came when general contractor I.D. <PERSON> Spassky </PERSON> warned that if the party does n't start showing it can solve citizens' problems, it can expect more of the same. `` People want to live better today,'' he said. `` The process of renewal of the economy at the least must move in parallel with political changes, but the prosperity of the people should outstrip it. Only then will the people believe us. And in the meantime, they wait for years and lose faith in perestroika.'' Across the nation in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Khabarovsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief V.S. <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> blamed his loss on the late President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> and his corrupt cronies. In an interview with <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> said people were sick of commands, and looked at all party leaders with the same distrust. <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> said a leaflet was circulated in <LOCATION> Khabarovsk </LOCATION> that said, `` A vote for <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> means a vote for the party which led our motherland into this dead end and now with the help of demogogic subterfuges, is trying to convince people it can lead them out of this situation.''
