<FIRST>r a AM-CountryMusic     04-06 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Country Music,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Folklife Collection At UNC Opens To The Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICA JOHNSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost 30 years ago, a young Australian who loved American country music died in a car accident in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, leaving behind 2,000 old 78s and boxes of correspondence with the pioneers who had made the records. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> never made it to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, but his collection did _ as he directed in his will. His legacy forms the nucleus of the Southern Folklife Collection that opened this week at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` In the past 20 years, historians have begun to look more and more toward folklife materials,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, an archivist of the collection. `` They're looking to sound recordings to provide a perspective on on the history of the South.'' In 1983, <ORGANIZATION> UNC </ORGANIZATION> bought the Edwards collection from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where it had been greatly expanded by acquisitions of more recordings and documents. UNC combined the purchase with the <ORGANIZATION> UNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Folklore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> to form the Southern Folklife Collection. With 38,000 items dating to 1906, the collection is being touted as one of the nation's three top resources for country music research, joining the <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Music is highly symbolic,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, chairman of the folklore curriculum at <ORGANIZATION> UNC </ORGANIZATION>. `` It encodes deep statements about your identity. It speaks of values that are woven into your life.'' The collection includes gospel, spirituals, blues, bluegrass, Cajun, ballads, native American, string band and country music _ everything from sermons recorded at a Primitive Baptist church to the Skillet Lickers' recording of the fiddle tune `` Cotton-Eyed Joe'' to <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON>' `` I'm Sick And Tired Of You, Little Darling.'' Researchers, musicians and other visitors also have access to books, videotapes and scrapbooks. Booths are available for listening to the tapes, and there's a sound studio to erase many of the flaws on old recordings. The people who have gathered in <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> through Saturday to mark the opening of the collection include musicians and the researchers and music professionals who have documented their lives. A concert Friday night will feature performers such as <PERSON> Etta </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a blues guitarist; <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Mainer </PERSON>, who in the 1920s was one of the first stars of country music; and <PERSON> Esteban </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, a Texan who calls himself the `` <PERSON> Jimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> of the accordion.'' Another scheduled proformer is <PERSON> Y </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngong </PERSON> <PERSON> Knul </PERSON>, a 67-year-old from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> now living in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> who performs a ritualized form of chanting. He symbolizes a musical direction that may be part of the traditional Southern music of tomorrow. `` There's starting to be a number of new ethnic groups moving into the South who have not been recorded as of yet,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. `` They're Hispanic and they're Vietnamese ... and they're playing their music. `` It's clearly not what what we've consider Southern traditional music up till now,'' he said. `` But the fact is ... in the next 100 years, it will be, and it's important to document it.''
