<HEAD>Employers' Group Calls For Importation of Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federation of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> employers urged the government Thursday to import foreign laborers to ease <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s acute labor shortage The group, called the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Working </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said it was essential to import contract laborers to avoid inflation and falling economic competitiveness. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> needs about 50,000 imported workers, most of them unskilled, to help fill an estimated 200,000 job vacancies, it said. The group's chairman, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, an executive at <ORGANIZATION> Jardine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Matheson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said there was danger <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> could lose it `` competitiveness in the manufacturing sector, the hotel industry and elsewhere'' because of the shortage of workers. The government said Tuesday it is considering easing restrictions on employment of foreign laborers. Under current policy, only foreign workers with skills not available locally are allowed to work in the colony. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s low unemployment rate, currently 1.3 percent, is considered a key factor behind the economy's growth slowing to an expected 6 percent this year, less than half the 1987 rate. The labor shortage is due to tight immigration laws and a steady drain of talent as the colony approaches its return to Chinese sovereignty in 1997. The report said the government should encourage automation and productivity through tax breaks and reducing red tape. It said bringing in workers on six-month to two-year contracts, similar to practices in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, would provide relief. The group also suggested the possibility of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> using workers who would commute daily from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
