<HEAD>Grant Will Help Veterans Pay Living Expenses While Under Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Until now, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans who came here to be treated for post-traumatic stress disorder were likely to encounter another kind of stress _ figuring out how to pay for living expenses during their seven-week stay. That's about to change. The Mid-Rio Grande chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> has been awarded more than $ 100,000 to help veterans and their families from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> pay rent and food costs while they are treated at an outpatient clinic at the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> hopes to serve about 70 veterans and their families during the one-year project, said <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> <PERSON> Waters </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> chapter's administrator of emergency services and disaster programs. `` I want it to be the tip of the iceberg kind of thing, where it could be increased,'' said Mrs. Waters, who hopes the grant will be renewed. `` We can reach them and help them into this -LRB- treatment -RRB- program that they would not be able to take part in if they had to worry about paying the rent or that basic kind of thing,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> was one of eight agencies nationwide awarded Agent Orange Class Assistance grants totaling more than $ 581,000 to help them serve <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans and their families. The March 30 awards were the first disbursements to service agencies from the settlement of a 1978 lawsuit against seven manufacturers of Agent Orange. In their class-action lawsuit, veterans alleged they got cancer and other illnesses because of exposure to the defoliant used by the military in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> in the 1960s. The $ 240 million settlement, upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last year, provides $ 170 million to be paid directly to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> veterans or their survivors; $ 52 million to agencies that serve veterans and their families; plus lesser amounts for veterans of other countries who served in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and for legal and administrative fees. The grants to service agencies were designed to reach veterans and their families who do not meet the eligibility requirements for direct payments, which are reserved for disabled veterans. The grants are not limited to agencies that treat Agent Orange-related problems. The $ 52 million fund for agencies is expected to grow with interest to $ 70million over the seven - to 10-year life of the program Mrs. Waters said the idea for rental and food assistance came because veterans from outside <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> contacted the local <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> for money to pay living expenses while in the city seeking treatment. `` It's been in my mind for a couple of years because we helped veterans when we could from <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> funding when they were here for the program,'' she said. `` They came and said they were taking part in the program and did n't have any more money for rent or gas or food.'' She said the grant `` really was a godsend'' because the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> was n't able to meet all the needs of the veterans it heard from. The chapter applied for $ 102,000 based on an estimate of veterans in the clinic and the chapter's experience in paying rent and food costs for homeless people, Ms. Waters said. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> treatment program, said she expects the grant will increase the number of veterans in the program from outside the <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> area. `` A major problem with any guys coming in from anywhere was the need for them to commute daily,'' she said. The clinic, which began operating in 1987, combines individual and group psychotherapy. Staff members try to avoid using medication because chemicals are only an artificial way of dealing with anxiety, <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. `` We directly address the patient's traumatic experience, bring back that event to the patient, then work through the feelings they've suppressed for the last 20 years,'' she said. The program, which she described as `` fairly intense,'' also includes counseling for married couples, anger management, problem solving and social skills, <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. The clinic has treated about 150 veterans and can handle 85 to 100 a year, she said.
