<FIRST>r w AM-TaxCompliance     04-06 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Compliance,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Taxpayers Not Adjusting to New Law, IRS Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many taxpayers are having trouble giving up lucrative deductions that were repealed or curtailed by the 1986 tax overhaul. A spot check by the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> of returns filed last year and early this year shows evidence of widespread non-compliance with parts of the new law. These include limitations on writing off investment and personal interest, on miscellaneous deductions such as union dues and on the treatment of rental losses. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> made the disclosure in announcing Thursday that it has broadened efforts to gauge how well taxpayers understand and comply with the new law. `` Recognizing that the 1986 act represents the most comprehensive change to the federal tax system in a quarter century and contained changes affecting almost every taxpayer, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will use the studies to assist taxpayers to better understand the new laws and help determine to what extent taxpayers are trying to circumvent various provisions of the new law,'' the agency said. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is so concerned about public reaction to the new law that it has set up teams in each of its 10 regional service centers to spot check returns as they are filed. Without such checks, the agency would have to wait until 1991 for comprehensive information from a sizable number of returns. A check of several thousand returns filed in 1988, the first year affected significantly by the new law, disclosed that many taxpayers did not follow tougher rules on treatment of losses from passive investments, rental losses, investment interest expenses and miscellaneous itemized deductions. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, head of audit planning for the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, said those issues were chosen as targets of the new effort because they involve large amounts of revenue, show up on many returns and were all changed significantly by the 1986 law. The first of about 150,000 returns filed this year that are expected to undergo spot checks show those same errors are being repeated. In addition, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said in an interview, many returns being filed this year attempted to avoid the reduction in the writeoff of consumer interest, in the deduction for business-related meals and entertainment and in depreciation of automobiles. In the past, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> generally would discover such non-compliance only through a formal audit, which usually would come about two years after a return was filed. With the new effort, the agency hopes to spot trends of non-compliance early and follow quickly with a campaign to educate the public. If the effort is successful, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> expects to see fewer taxpayers making these mistakes and fewer returns being audited on those issues. `` We want to fix as many of these things as we can without doing audits on people,'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. `` If we can do these as part of -LRB- returns -RRB- processing, that's what we want to do.'' The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has not yet estimated how much money is being lost by the government because of non-compliance with the 1986 tax changes. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said the spot checks are likely to find numerous cases in which taxpayers cheated themselves by misreading parts of the new law. Those taxpayers will be notified, he emphasized. Information from the spot checks will be used to determine whether the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> needs to change its tax forms, instructions or publications to clear up confusion resulting from the law changes, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said.
