<HEAD>1989 Predicted Worst Year Yet For Soviet Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is facing its toughest year yet and could degenerate into `` economic chaos'' without urgent reforms, a newspaper said Thursday. `` The bony hand of hunger for products is quite capable of strangling perestroika,'' the Soviet program of economic restructuring, journalist <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> wrote in a front-page article in the daily <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>. By putting off painful reforms, economists are ruining the chances for those reforms to succeed, said <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>, who specializes in economic affairs. He cited the need to deal urgently with the Soviet budget deficit and shortages of consumer goods. <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>'s calls for more rapid economic change have appeared in other top journals. The sooner real reform is introduced the better, `` because otherwise we'll have to be introducing economic reform under the conditions of economic chaos,'' he said. The government could have begun raising prices on plentiful, easily substituted items, but it is too late because virtually everything is in short supply, he said. An institute on consumer demand found that 211 food products, only 23 could be bought freely, he said. The rest require connections with the sellers, overpayment or are rationed. Strategists promise tough reforms after an initial period of heightened output of consumer goods, but there is no reason to expect any such increase, <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> said. `` On the contrary, one can expect that the year 1989 will be the most unsuccessful of all those we have lived through,'' he said. Along with the announced budget deficit of $ 58 billion and an additional $ 102 billion in loans to state enterprises that are losing money, the unexpected expense of earthquakes in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tadzhikistan </LOCATION> will cripple the 1989 economy even further, <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> said. He said inflation is running at 4 percent to 5 percent annually, much higher than official figures. `` Today we have to choose between only two realities: either relatively stable prices with minor inflation of about 6 percent and empty shelves, or quickly rising prices and goods in the stores,'' he said. <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON>'s prescriptions for fixing the economy included cuts in military spending, which he placed at nearly 20 percent of national income, and two or three years of importing giant stocks of goods from the West. The imports could be sold at 10 times their cost and thus both help to balance the state budget and satisfy consumer demand, <PERSON> Selyunin </PERSON> proposed. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other leaders have said they oppose such massive imports, preferring to spend money on modernizing industry instead.
