<HEAD>Some Governing Party Members Seek Resignation of Takeshita</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> faces pressure from some members of his own party to resign to halt damage to the party from a stock-profiteering scandal, politicians and news reports said Thursday. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who acknowledged receiving nearly $ 400,000 in political contributions from the company at the center of the scandal, has vowed to remain in power despite opposition calls for his resignation and public opinion polls that show as few as 9 percent of Japanese support his government. The news reports said Thursday about 40 influential members of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have decided to form the faction, which demands all those linked to the scandal _ including party leaders _ step down. `` The situation has reached a critical stage,'' they quoted <PERSON> Shizuka </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamei </PERSON>, a leading member of the group, as saying. `` The present <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is not capable of carrying out self-purification.'' The group also demands the government call former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> for questioning by legislators on possible links with the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an information conglomerate that allegedly used stock bargains to seek favors. Opposition parties are boycotting parliamentary deliberations on the budget, which began Saturday, to back their demands for <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>'s testimony. On Wednesday, a group of 41 junior party members formed a faction to demand the government push political reforms. `` Prime Minister <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and Mr. <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> should accept the guilt and take appropriate measures to satisfy the people,'' said faction leade