<FIRST>r w AM-ConsumerCredit     04-06 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Credit,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Debt Grows By $4.22 Billion in February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans took out $ 4.22 billion more in consumer debt than they paid off in February, the slowest pace of growth in four months, the government said Thursday in a report consistent with other signs the economy may be slowing. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the February increase in consumer credit was down slightly from January's rise of $ 4.37 billion and was the smallest monthly gain since a $ 3.91 billion increase in October. Growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards strengthened in February, while the gain in auto loans was slightly smaller than in January. Borrowing through bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate also slowed while mobile home lending declined. Analysts said the restrained growth in debt indicates consumers may be becoming more cautious about their buying plans and is in line with other signs that the economy is slowing down in the seventh year of its record peacetime expansion. `` It does n't suggest any great retrenchment by consumers but it does indicate somewhat more caution,'' said economist <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` It's consistent with this gradually accumulating evidence that the economy is beginning to cool off.'' Consumer spending is closely watched as a barometer of economic health because it accounts for two-thirds of economic activity. Most government reports on the economy's performance in February pointed downward, although 1989 began with strong momentum. Analysts expect the economy to slow this year as the recovery ages and the nation responds to a yearlong campaign by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to push up interest rates to restrain growth and keep inflation in check. February's 7.5 percent rise in the seasonally adjusted annual rate of credit growth was down from 7.9 percent in January and 7.8 percent in December. For all of 1988, consumer debt rose 8.75 percent. Auto loans rose $ 2.1 billion in February, an 8.6 percent annual rate of growth, following a $ 2.13 billion increase during January. Automobile sales have been weak this year, with business held down by rising interest rates. Automakers in recent weeks have launched a new round of cash rebates and low-interest financing programs in an effort to boost sales and avoid large production cutbacks. Growth in the category of debt that includes credit cards rose $ 1.6 billion in February, a 10.3 percent annual rate of growth. That followed a January increase of $ 1.02 billion, a 6.6 percent annual rate. Mobile home debts dropped $ 59 million in February, a 2.8 percent rate of decline, after rising $ 50 million in January. Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate rose by $ 569 million in February, a 4.1 percent rate of growth, after rising $ 1.17 billion in January. The various changes left total consumer debt at a seasonally adjusted $ 674.78 billion in February, up 8.1 percent from a year earlier.
