 President-elect <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> says he represents rightists who think of themselves as modern conservatives, not exponents of their party's early neo-fascism As <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> meets President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Friday, many question whether his faction of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> is dominant and whether he can control reputedly sinister elements of the party. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> takes office June 1. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which gives <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salvador </ORGANIZATION> about $ 1.5 million a day in aid, has said it will keep a close watch on human rights abuses under the right-wing party, known as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>. Officials also have tied continued aid to an improved record. Even his antagonists consider <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> personally upstanding, and most accept his avowed commitment to furthering democracy in a nation ravaged by nine years of civil war. He was faced with an important test March 31. An outgoing <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge ruled that two military men and a landowner implicated in an kidnap-for-profit ring in the early 1980s were illegally detained and must be freed. All three, along with five fugitives absolved by the judge, were cronies of <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, a dismissed major of army intelligence who founded <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> in 1981 and retains great influence in it. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> acted decisively. He brought pressure to bear on the judiciary, got the judge's order revoked and kept two of the three suspects in jail. New arrest warrants were issued for the man released and for the five d'Aubuisson associates implicated in the ring. A ranking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy official said of <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s first human rights test: `` He passed with flying colors.'' Critics of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> say <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, a wealthy landowner educated at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is a pseudo-democratic veneer on an apparatus linked to rightist death squads that killed tens of thousands of alleged leftists in the early 1980s. <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s anthem, broadcast incessantly during the campaign, still says: `` <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> will be the tomb where the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> will all end up.'' The president-elect denies being a front man and says <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, who is an Arena legislator and leads the majority bloc in the unicameral legislature, will not have a post in the executive branch. `` There should be no doubt that it is I who will run the government,'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said after winning the March 19 election. He is 41, a coffee-grower, businessman and champion athlete who came late to politics and rose to prominence in Arena after <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON> lost the 1984 presidential election. `` Be assured that I entered politics only because of the country's grave crisis and am not motivated by personal ambition,'' he said in a radio advertisement during his campaign. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> campaigned on a platform of `` capitalism for the masses'' and an end to the civil war. He has said he is willing to talk with leftist rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, but `` we will not negotiate our political platform, or a share of power. We will not negotiate democracy.'' Monsignor <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, auxiliary archbishop of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, said recently the Arena victory was likely `` to augment the level of violence, because they are advocates of escalation of the war.'' The new president's position is that he will offer the rebels terms for laying down arms and entering the democratic process, and will increase military pressure if they refuse. Rebel leaders say that amounts to a call for surrender. They say they will be the ones to intensify the war, showing the country to be ungovernable without their participation.
