<SECOND>AM-Senate Bicentennial,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Celebrates Its First Two Centuries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, told it `` is a guardian of tradition without becoming a barrier to change,'' celebrated its first two centuries of history on Thursday, recalling its faltering beginnings and noting its many milestones. April 6, 1789, was the date that the first <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, meeting in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, finally reached a quorum _ and thus was able to start conducting business _ after a frustrating month of failing to do so. `` History oozes from these walls,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, as the day of commemoration began in the Old Senate Chamber in the Capitol with the issuing of a postage stamp displaying the gilt shield and eagle still suspended over the presiding officer's chair The eagle and shield were there during speeches on the old chamber's floor which served the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from 1810 to 1859, and can be seen in 19th century prints involving three famous senators of the era: <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Those three senators and the roles they played in the period before the Civil War were invoked repeatedly as past and former senators hailed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as an institution. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader, said the sense of history in the old <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hall, and in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s present chamber first occupied in 1859, is so strong that at times one can truly `` smell the marble.'' Nearly 20 former senators _ including <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansfield </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> _ joined senators in the current 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the ceremonies. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> celebrated the quorum bicentennial session of that body on Tuesday. Former Sen. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON>, a Democrat from <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, said that the legacy of the early <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is the art of the American political compromise. `` Today compromise is woven into constitutional fabric of the nation,'' <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> said. Although many senators past and present have regarded compromise as morally wrong, <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> said it is politically essential. `` Compromise, in my judgment, is getting a bad rap,'' <PERSON> Eagleton </PERSON> said. `` Without it we screech to a halt, paralyzed by intransigence.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> session began at 11 a.m., the hour of the first session two centuries ago. With the conclusion of the ceremony's first half in the old chamber, senators formed a procession to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s present meeting place down the hall. Senior senators from the states answered the roll call, beginning with <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, which became the first state in 1787, and continuing to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, which in 1959 became the 50th to join the union. When <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s name was called, Republican <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> gave this response: `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> was not the first state to be admitted, but it was the first to secede'' in 1860. After the Civil War, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> returned to the union in 1868. Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, noted <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>'s description of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as a stage, and recalled some of the drama the present chamber has witnessed, including the one-vote defeat of the attempt to oust President <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> during Reconstruction after the Civil War, and the rejection of President <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s effort to bring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into the League of Nations after World War I. Senate Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said that while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has undergone many changes over the years, it remains a place where the rights of the minority are protected and speech can remain virtually unlimited. `` It is a guardian of tradition without becoming a barrier to change,'' he said. Senators moved in and out of the ceremonies to spirited <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Sousa </PERSON> marches played by the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> band. A tourist asked a doorman: `` Does a band play every day the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> meets?'' `` No,'' the doorman replied. `` Only once every 200 years.''
