<FIRST>r w AM-Beef-Fat     04-06 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beef-Fat,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Beef Industry Responding to Consumer Demands for Less
Fat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers prefer less fat in their steaks and hamburger, and the beef industry has responded well to those demands, two <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M University scientists said Thursday. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Savell </PERSON> said further progress can be expected in the future as attention continues to be drawn to health issues, notably the dietary linkage between fats and high levels of blood cholesterol. But <PERSON> Savell </PERSON> told a conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cattlemen </ORGANIZATION>'s Association that if he had to send cattle producers and the beef industry a note from the teacher, it might say: `` Excellent progress made in making product fit consumers' needs. Keep working on leanness, convenience and cost, value. Remember to maintain taste, or consumers will go elsewhere.'' The beef industry drew praise from <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, who agreed that less fat is being sold to consumers. `` I think they have done more than many other industries to recognize the dangers of excessive fat consumption and take steps to inform consumers about that,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. But selling meat is also a business, he said, and `` the beef industry wants to recover its market share; they have lost it steadily to chicken and poultry in general over the past 10 years.'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said that occurred `` largely because of consumer perception of beef as a high-fat food.'' It was just a year ago that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> released a study by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M, led by <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Savell </PERSON>, that showed the trimmable fat on retail cuts of beef had been reduced 27 percent in two years. The $ 45,000 study, paid for by the beef industry and <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, showed that the average thickness of fat on steaks and roasts from primal cuts, or the major wholesale cuts of beef, was 0.14 inch, while the average for all cuts, from chuck roast to stew meat, was 0.11 inch, or less than one-eighth of an inch. Most retailers have been using a quarter-inch beef fat trim, or less, since 1985, compared with a standard of half an inch before that, according to the industry. At the conference, <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said consumers have indicated they would pay for more closely trimmed beef, preferably with external fat of less than one-eighth inch. Internal fat, or marbling, has been a factor in the taste of beef, and <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said this still is important to consumers. The challenge, he said, is take fat off, not out of beef. Cross said that <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M meat scientists are currently working with human medicine researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on projects aimed at further improvements in the healthfulness of beef. The work includes modification of the fatty acid content of meat product through changes in cattle feeds and products themselves. Fatty acids can potentially elevate cholesterol levels in human blood. But <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said that even now, only 27 percent of the total fat in beef is the type of saturated fatty acid that can raise cholesterol. <PERSON> Savell </PERSON> told of recent research on the composition of cooked as well as raw beef with reduced or no external fat. For example, if a slice of beef with all the fat trimmed off is cooked, the fat content of the interior meat is reduced by 20 percent from a slice with a quarter-inch layer of fat. That is because less fat migrates from the outside into the meat tissue. `` When you trim the fat off a steak that has a half inch of fat, you get rid of half the total cholesterol,'' <PERSON> Savell </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
