<HEAD>Ban on Solidarity to be Lifted Immediately</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``The agreement ...'' with 2 grafs with more
on registration.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government minister said Thursday the seven-year ban on Solidarity would be lifted immediately, and <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> urged supporters to put their `` political victory'' into action by organizing nationwide. `` The process of legalization of Solidarity should be completed between April 15 and April 20,'' said Sports Minister <PERSON> Aleksander </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwasniewski </PERSON>, a chief negotiator for the communist government in two months of talks with the opposition that concluded Wednesday in a broad accord. <PERSON> Kwasniewski </PERSON> said the Sejm, or parliament, would meet Friday to enact the agreements on trade union freedoms, economic reforms and political changes, including creation of the first freely elected legislative body in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, looking relaxed at a news conference after a grueling week of negotiations, outlined the tasks his independent trade union faces. But he warned the agreement could lead to disaster if <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> failed to take advantage of the changes. `` The most important task for today is to write applications immediately all over the country to provincial governors and city mayors so we get the technical possibility to organize as soon as possible,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. The agreement allows Solidarity to organize on a national, regional and local level after parliament makes the necessary changes in the labor law to permit more than one legal trade union at a workplace. On the national level, the union plans to form an organizing committee as early as this weekend to apply for formal registration by submitting a new union charter in court, said top Solidarity adviser <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>. `` Today we as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> have a great victory, but a political victory _ a theoretical one which may turn out to be a victory or a disaster if we are not able to make use of it,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. `` If we are not able to work in the economic field to have more, produce more and better and in the political field to represent ourselves well ... nice slogans will only stay slogans,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. The government daily Rzeczpospolita called the agreements sealed by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, the interior minister, a breakthrough that created a chance that must not be wasted by `` false solutions, sham ambitions or ignorance of realities.'' <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciosek </PERSON>, a Politburo member and participant in the talks, said the agreement was a step toward reforms undertaken by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, but it would not solve all of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s problems `` These reforms have made the prospect of satisfying the working class much closer,'' <PERSON> Ciosek </PERSON> said. `` In spite of what I said before, one should not expect that the agreement reached should eliminate all concerns and troubles.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appeared unconcerned by the apparent lack of reaction by Poles to the restoration of the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union, which claimed 10 million members and ignited that nation's spirit during its 16-month legal existence before being crushed under martial law in December 1981. `` I went on the hotel balcony today and watched people's behavior I met with great sympathy, almost everyone waved, but also with a lot of doubt,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. He said the union had trouble before with expectations that were too high, so today's skepticism is good. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he expected Solidarity to attract 5 million to 7 million members, but that he would like to see at least three competing trade unions. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and his advisers have said the shift in the attitude of the Polish leadership toward Solidarity is partially due to changes in the political climate in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he would like to see what is happening in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for himself and added: `` I would not like to disturb perestroika and reforms. That country is reforming itself as far as we hear. ... We want to solve our -LRB- problems -RRB- and not disturb others.'' He later flew to his home in the port city of <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where Solidarity was founded, and told reporters the union would like to use the Monopol Hotel in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> as its national headquarters. <PERSON> Kwasniewski </PERSON> said the government had urged local and regional authorities to support the registration process of new unions and provide them with office space. Authorities proposed the talks in August during the year's second nationwide wave of strikes When work stoppages appeared again this year, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appealed for calm to give the negotiations a chance. Both sides have expressed hope the solutions reached at the talks that began Feb. 6 will repair the economy and revive the dispirited population. In addition to Solidarity, authorities agreed to restore legal status to the farmers' union Rural Solidarity and the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, all banned during martial law. In exchange, the opposition agreed to participate in June elections to the 460-member Sejm that guarantee the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies a 65 percent majority. But at the same time, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> will have its first democratic elections since World War II, creating a new 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. A presidency also will be created, to be elected by the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION>. The president would be elected this year for a six-year term and the post is expected to go to Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, due to his party's dominance in the larger Sejm.
