<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite pleas for help from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it was too early to advance a new drought relief package to aid winter wheat growers facing potential losses from dry weather and temperature extremes. `` We do n't know there is going to be a widespread disaster,'' <PERSON> Ewen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant secretary for economics, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. Frustrated by the wait-and-see approach, a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> lawmaker introduced legislation to extend drought assistance approved last year by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to farmers of winter wheat planted in 1988. `` It is my people. We are suffering. We were able to work with corn country last year. It is our time,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Kan </LOCATION>., who represents a 58-county district considered one of the prime wheat-growing regions in the nation According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, the winter wheat outlook is bleak in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, traditionally the nation's largest producer. At the start of the month, 70 percent of the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> wheat crop was rated poor to very poor. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> normally accounts for 17 percent of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat production and 35 percent of the nation's hard red winter wheat, the main bread wheat. In testimony to the wheat, soybeans and feed grains subcommittee, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> officials conceded that drought could sharply reduce harvests in portions of the major winter wheat states of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. However, they held hope that spring rains could rescue part of the crop. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief meterologist, said the next 30 to 60 days will be critical. He said the 90-day weather outlook suggested near-normal rainfall in much of the Wheat Belt across the the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, although below normal rainfall is expected in the short term. Because the winter wheat crop is developing later than usual this year, <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON> said, `` we have a mixed picture.'' `` It's just a little premature to start to write the crop down to any specific level,'' said <PERSON> Strommen </PERSON>. `` We simply have to watch and wait for the development and the timing and distribution of rainfall in the next two months.'' Lawmakers unsuccessfully pressed <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to support a new legislative relief package or extending the 1988 drought assistance programs to the 1989 wheat crop. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> `` does n't want to do anything precipitous.'' `` We will have to monitor the situation and see if it rains and see how bad it is,'' he said. For the major winter wheat states, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said, 31 percent of the overall crop was rated poor to very poor compared to 8 percent last year at this time. According to a `` highly tentative'' projection by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, total 1989 wheat production could be about 2.45 billion bushels, a 35 percent boost from last year's drought-reduced harvest. At the hearing, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnittker </PERSON>, a private agricultural analyst, estimated a harvest of 2.25-2 .3 billion bushels He warned that a poor <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> winter wheat crop would drastically shrink already small grain stockpiles and pose `` a serious threat to world food sufficiency and price stability.''
