<HEAD>Opposition Makes Demands of Victorious Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives of Salvadoran rebels challenged the newly elected Arena party Thursday to declare its administration a `` government of transition'' or face a deepening of the nine-year-old war in the Central American country. <PERSON> Guadelupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON> of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> said the proposal was being announced in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> because president-elect <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> is here for talks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Altschul </PERSON>, a representative of the political opposition commission of the rebel group, said the proposal was presented Thursday to representatives of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> and other Salvadoran factions. He said he knew of no response. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> has a news conference scheduled Friday morning and will meet with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the afternoon. Asked what would happen if <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> rejects the proposal, <PERSON> Altschul </PERSON> said, `` We hope it is not rejected. Unless there is a negotiated settlement of the war, there is only going to be an ungovernable country; there is only going to be a deepening of the war.'' Meanwhile in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> the leftist guerrillas attacked the 4th Army brigade headquarters and the headquarters of army engineers, authorities said. Three soldiers and three guerrillas were reported killed and 10 people wounded. More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most of them civilians, have been killed during the nine-year war against the U.S.-supported government. The rebels have stepped up attacks recently to protest the election of <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, a right-wing businessman who was the candidate of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, in an election March 9. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> is scheduled to take office June 1. <PERSON> Altschul </PERSON> told reporters that <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, named for its initials in Spanish, `` has made it very clear that it will follow a policy of massacres and total war and has given no indication of a serious disposition toward peace.'' He said the rebels would seek a response from <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> to demands that it stop assassinations, respect nationalization of banks and other steps taken by its predecessors and abandon its insistence that the guerrillas surrender. He said this would be `` a first step to start serious negotiations.'' `` In order to resolve the problem of the war in a definitive manner, it is necessary to revise the constitution and for the future <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> government to declare itself a government of transition,'' the proposal said. It called for elections in which the army would be confined to barracks and the rebel military forces also kept away from voting places for three days before, during and after the voting. It called for the rebel faction to `` participate directly as a political force in these elections with our flag and in coalition with other parties which may be disposed to participate together with us.'' It said that commanders and officers implicated in `` political crimes and massacres which have been causes of the war'' must be brought to justice. The rebels also demanded that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid be cut off and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> advisors withdrawn. Elections would be held within six months after initiation of a cease fire.
