group of Republican congressmen said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should become more directly involved in the matter and put a federal agency in overall charge of the effort. At a news conference called by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> said he has received offers from people willing to travel to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to help, but has not found any government agency that can provide information on what steps such volunteers should take. While the debate continued on what steps need to be taken to protect wildlife, fish and the ecology of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, officials agreed the early response to the March 24 accident in which the Exxon Valdez supertanker ran aground, spilling more than 10 million gallons of oil, was largely bungled and probably was inadequate even if events had run more smoothly. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel the petroleum industry's emergency reaction plan and the environmental impact analysis in connection with the Alaskan pipeline did not contemplate such a massive spill. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said that while all is being done now that can be done to deal with the spill, the response on the first two days after the accident was inadequate. `` They had n't planned for a catstrophe of this magnitude,'' he told the senators. The contingency plan, for example, called for booms to be put around the stricken tanker within five hours, but the booms were not in place until 12 hours after the accident and then did not hold because of strong winds, <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., said the basic response plan was faulty, noting that when it was developed the largest oil spill anticipated was 74,000 barrels The oil that gushed from the Exxon Valdez was more than three times that amount and came out at a rate of 50,000 barrels an hour, according to administration officials.
