<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The operator of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline terminal announced Thursday that it will immediately require random drug and alcohol testing on all vessels using the terminal. The action was one of several announced by <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of seven oil companies that owns and operates the Valdez terminal and the 800-mile pipeline. <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> has been criticized for its slow response to the nation's worst oil spill. The tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> took on a load at <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> on March 24 and hours later ran aground, releasing more than 10 million gallons of crude oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The ship's captain, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, is charged with operating the vessel while drunk. <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> said in a news release that it would require tanker owners and operators to institute random drug and alcohol testing. It also said it would require tugboat escorts for all entering and departing vessels to a point beyond <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>, where the Exxon Valdez ran aground. The state this week drafted an emergency order that, if signed, would require <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> immediately to take several steps to correct problems with its oil-spill response program. Some of those steps, including the purchase of additional booms, dispersants and other cleanup equipment, were included in <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement Thursday. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, commissioner of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>, was expected to sign the order, Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> said. The draft order sharply criticizes <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION>'s initial response to the spill, saying it failed to comply with its spill contingency plan and took too long to deploy equipment. The order says `` continued operation of <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION>'s marine terminal and tanker traffic at the current crude-oil flow rate creates a substantial risk of an additional oil spill'' in the sound. <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> said a task force of oil company officials will make additional recommendations to improve spill response. `` We sincerely regret the environmental tragedy in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> and pledge to do everything feasible to prevent another such accident from happening,'' the news release said. `` A painful lesson has been learned.''
