<HEAD>Soviets Buy Corn; Chinese, Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been sold wheat at subsidized prices, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Officials said that the Soviet purchase was for 400,000 metric tons of corn to be delivered this year and that the wheat sale to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was for 300,000 tons. Both deliveries are scheduled for this year. More than 2.7 million tons have been purchased since the Soviets rsumed buying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn on March 28 after a layoff of almost three months. The latest sales brought total corn sold to the Soviets for 1988-89 to almost 13 million tons. Additionally, sales include 4 million tons of wheat, 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal and 507,400 tons of grain sorghum. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 400,000 tons of corn woud be about 15.8 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.45 per bushel at the farm level, according to the latest <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> five-day average, meaning that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $ 39 million. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reddington </PERSON>, acting general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the wheat was part of 2 million tons authorized Feb. 27 for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP. Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in selected overseas markets and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. The latest sale boosted to about 8.5 million tons the amount of wheat sold to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for 1988-89 delivery under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Reddington </PERSON> said the latest sales were handled by <ORGANIZATION> Garnac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Bunge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 100,000, and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 100,000 He said the wheat will carry an average subsidy rate of $ 6.33 per ton, or about 17 cents a bushel. About 910,000 tons are still available under the current authorization. The 300,000 tons of wheat would be about 11 million bushels and, at recent prices of about $ 3.96 per bushel, would have a farm value of around $ 44 million.
