<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee voted Thursday to end the remaining price controls on natural gas in 1993. A decade ago, the action of the energy and power subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> would have followed battles between consuming and producing states. Memories of those battles led <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and its committees to ignore the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's almost annual requests for removal of controls. Thursday, it took only 12 -LCB- minutes for the subcommittee to approve, by voice vote and without dissent, the bill sponsored by 22 of its 23 members. A previous decontrol episode in 1985 saw prices collapse, confounding predictions of a pocketbook-bashing `` fly-up'' of prices. Many analysts now believe gas prices are determined by oil prices because many industrial users can switch between the two. Most believe decontrol will have little immediate effect if demand does not increase as ceiling prices frequently are well above spot prices. The last major gas pricing battle in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> came in 1978, when harsh winters, diversion of gas into unregulated intrastate markets and soaring oil prices all combined to curtail gas deliveries to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and Northeast. To encourage new production, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted several different prices for gas according to source, such as tight sands or very deep wells, and permitted those prices to rise with inflation. It also provided that much of that gas would be decontrolled in 1985, as it was. But gas from existing wells was to remain under price controls. That gas is a smaller percentage of the supply every year and today is 25 percent to 30 percent of gas flowing through pipelines, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has declared that the ceiling price of certain gas could rise to the price of the most expensive category. That ceiling price, which rises with inflation, is now $ 2.79 per thousand cubic feet. The March average spot price in major producing states, according to the newsletter <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION>, was $ 1.44. Some old gas is sold for 30 cents. The bill does not abrogate contracts. Some contracts provide for market pricing under decontrol but others do not.
</TEXT>
