<TEXT>
 Backers of a bill to curb the amount of commercials shown on TV shows for children said Thursday that broadcasters have stepped up the pitches on such programs since ad limits were lifted five years ago. Kids are being exposed to as much as 42 percent more toy, cereal and candy advertising per hour than adults, as advertisers target `` a particularly vulnerable audience,'' Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> hearing An independent station in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> is inserting as many as 14 minutes of commericals into each hour of kids' shows, compared with an average eight minutes for adult network programs, <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee that he chairs. `` We have a duty to see to it that this child audience is protected from wave after wave of exploitive commercials,'' he said. Prior to 1984, when the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> lifted commercial limits on kids' TV shows, the amount of ads on network children's programs was at or below the 9 -LCB- minute-per-hour rules that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had established in 1974, <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said. Since 1984, `` commercial time has been on the rise, with stations at two of the networks now offering as many as 11 minutes per hour of commercial matter,'' he said. <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said the government must stem `` endless streams'' of TV commercials on children's shows because broadcasters are not regulating themselves. But <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ