<HEAD>FTC Judge Finds Kraft Unintentionally Made False Claims for Cheese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> unintentionally advertised falsely that its Kraft Singles cheese slices contain as much calcium as five ounces of milk and more than imitation cheese, according to a ruling of a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> administrative law judge released Thursday. <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> said it did not believe the ads were misleading and would appeal the ruling to the full commission. One of the challenged ads said: `` Imitation slices use hardly any milk. But <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> has five ounces per slice. So her little bones get calcium they need to grow.'' The judge, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, said the ad implied that the slice contained as much calcium as five ounces of milk and did not mention that 30 percent of the calcium in the milk is lost in processing. Also, he said, the ads can be taken as implying `` that imitation slices which, they state, use hardly any milk, contain less calcium than <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> <PERSON> Singles </PERSON>.'' In fact, almost all imitation and non-dairy cheese contains just as much calcium as the real thing, he said. However, <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> `` did not intend to make'' misrepresentations and it was `` debatable'' whether the company should have known that false claims could be inferred from the ads, he said. `` The advertisements ... were developed by <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> in response to the success of non-dairy imitation and substitute cheese slices, and were not intended to convey express deceptive claims.'' He ordered the company not to misrepresent the nutritional content of its cheese slices in the future. In <LOCATION> Glenview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, company spokesman <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> was pleased that the judge recognized `` there was no intent on the part of <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> to mislead the public.'' `` Copy testing that we've done demonstrates that consumers do not receive the implied message'' as stated in <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s ruling, <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> is `` confident that the integrity of the advertising will be upheld'' by the commission, he said. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverglade </PERSON>, attorney for Science in the Public Interest, the advocacy group which asked the commission to look into the matter in 1985, said he was pleased with the decision. `` It may represent a reawakening of the federal government to problems of misleading health claims in food advertising,'' he said.
</TEXT>
