mil secessionist war and a violent Sinhalese backlash have claimed more than 12,500 lives. The latest violence came barely 24 hours after the government announced a unilateral one-week cease-fire, beginning Tuesday. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said Wednesday: `` It -LRB- the cease-fire -RRB- will be a unilateral declaration by the government and will cover military operations by both <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and Indian armies against Sinhalese and Tamil terrorists.'' The government on Thursday also released 13 political prisoners as part of a peace proposal offered to Tamils and Sinhalese militants. After receiving a pardon from President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, the prisoners walked out of a maximum-security prison, about three miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The prisoners were Tamils convicted under anti-terrorist laws and serving sentences ranging from five to 15 years, said <PERSON> Velupillai </PERSON> <PERSON> Balakumar </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a Tamil group. Last week, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> offered Tamil and Sinhalese militants unconditional amnesty, seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and money for surrendered weapons if they stopped fighting. Neither Sinhalese militants nor the Tamil rebels have responded positively to the peace overtures. On Wednesday, Sinhalese militants called a nationwide strike to commemorate a failed uprising against the government 18 years ago. The strike was viewed as a rejection of the peace offer. Meanwhile, two opposition leaders said the cease-fire announcement would not be fruitful unless the government held negotiations with extremist leaders. Sinhalese militants started the current campaign to bring down the government after the July 1987 peace accord was signed, saying it gave too many concessions to the minority community. The predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. Sinhalese Buddhists make up 75 percent and control the government and the military. Tamil militants allege their community is discriminated against by the Sinhalese in jobs and education.
