<HEAD>Soviet Confirms Jets to Libya, Denies They Threaten Neighbors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> confirmed Thursday that it delivered fighter-bombers to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> last month, but said they were defensive aircraft and did not have the range to threaten <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said the total was `` around half a dozen,'' not 12 to 15 as claimed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The issue appeared to cast a shadow over the otherwise warm, constructive tone of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s talks with Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. With <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> reports of the bomber sale capturing headlines in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for an explanation and got none, her spokesman said. Her foreign secretary, Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, also raised the matter with his Soviet counterpart, <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> responded by mentioning British arms sales to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> said his government was concerned because <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> is a terrorist state, said the British spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> told a news conference he did not know about the sale, but later went on television to confirm elements of the report while seeking to minimize its significance. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sources have said the aircraft are SU-24 Fencers, which can fly within an 800-mile radius without refueling, far enough to reach <LOC