<HEAD>Vets Who Built Clinic For Former Enemy Return To Happy Greetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans flew home from <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> to a greeting of confetti, hugs and kisses Thursday after building a 14-room clinic for their former enemies with $ 50,000 in donated money. `` Boy, we did n't get a greeting like this when we came back from the war,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> veteran <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, among the six volunteers who returned to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after nearly four months in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The veterans, along with about 30 Vietnamese they paid $ 1 a day each, erected a one-story, 2,500-square-foot building at <LOCATION> Vung </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tau </LOCATION>, some 60 miles from <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, formerly <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>. The veterans said they watched with pride Saturday while local politicians made speeches under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Vietnamese flags in a champagne-toasted ceremony to mark the finish of the project. The unusual mission left <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> feeling much better about himself than he did after serving a year in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 41, was the job foreman on what he and his buddies called the `` Veterans Vietnam Restoration Project,'' an idea that originated with a Veterans of Foreign Wars contingent at <LOCATION> Garberville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` It was,'' he said, `` out of a sense of purpose, to do something kind for the Vietnamese people,'' he said, but not because he felt he had hurt them in the war. `` I do n't lay that personal guilt on myself,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> declared. `` But I have problems secondary to that. There was something about the Vietnamese people I had to do.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said he did n't have to come home from the war to conclude, as he did, that there was something wrong with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` In my first three months in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> I noticed it was a crazy war and it was wrong and that some day we would have to make up for it,'' he said. The volunteers, who had collected $ 50,000 in a funding drive that began last year, were given housing by the Vietnamese government, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. But they had to buy their own food and other necessities. They ran into some surprises in building their clinic. Instead of using concrete blocks they had to use small locally made bricks. The basic design, which called for a 1,500-square-foot building, was changed to 2,500 square feet at the insistence of local politicians. And every day, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said, he had to deal with local officials who had to approve of everything that was to be done. `` We brought some tools and experience, but we did n't realize we could n't get power to the job site,'' he said. `` We did n't realize water was rationed so we could n't mix materials. We did n't realize everything had to be done by hand.''
