<HEAD>Air Force Says Problem Does Not Stall Return of Bombers to the Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the in-flight loss of escape hatches on two B-1B bombers would lead to more frequent inspections of the equipment in the future but the problem had not stalled the return of the bombers to the air. Col. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said 60 of the 97 B-1Bs in the fleet had been cleared for air operations by late Thursday and that all of the B-1Bs scheduled for training flights Thursday or Thursday night would be permitted to fly. The B-1B fleet has been slowly returning to the air this week after being grounded in the wake of a March 27 incident at <ORGANIZATION> Dyess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. That incident involved the failure of gears that move the wings on the swing-wing bomber. As that grounding order was being lifted this week, two B-1Bs experienced unusual problems with the same escape hatch suddenly blowing off during training flights. The first hatch-blowing incident occurred about 11 a.m. Tuesday as the jet was climbing from a low-altitude exercise near the <LOCATION> Texas-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> border. The 3-foot by 4-foot hatch blew off at about 12,500 feet. Then at about 11:45 a.m. Wednesday, a hatch in the same place on another B-1B blew off at about 19,000 feet as the jet flew over La Junta Training Range near <LOCATION> Pueblo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. No one was injured and both airplanes made routine landings But the incidents caused the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to order another inspection of each plane before they took off on training flights. <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had not recovered either of the two hatches, but that inspections of the other planes in the fleet suggested routine opening and closing of the hatches during maintenance can gradually throw the locking latches `` beyond normal tolerance levels.'' `` We're going to perform the inspection on these hatches more often,'' <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said. `` It's part of the growing process with a new plane. As equipment matures, you have to adjust your maintenance and inspection schedules.'' The spokesman added technicians also had discovered that by painting a small stripe across the hatch inside the plane, it was possible to provide an easy visual cue to the crew to make sure a hatch is shut tight. As for the problem that prompted the grounding, <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said that 87 B-1Bs had undergone the required inspection by Thursday and 60 had been cleared for flight. Ten are awaiting inspection. In the case of the other 27, he continued, a gear box that handles drive shafts that help to move the wings has been removed and shipped to the <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the maker, for inspection. The spokesman declined to predict when the entire fleet would be back in the air.
