<HEAD>UN Experts Say Soviets Will Allow International Appeals On Human
Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> human rights officials said Thursday the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has agreed to sign an accord allowing its citizens to take human rights complaints directly to international investigators. They said the Soviets would sign the Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. Soviet acceptance of the document would be an extension of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s declaration in December that human rights should be given new emphasis in international affairs. <PERSON> Rajsoomer </PERSON> <PERSON> Lallah </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> associated with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pocar </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> of the committee told reporters the notice was unofficial and the Soviets had not said when they would sign the protocol. <PERSON> Pocar </PERSON> said he received the assurances during `` a workshop at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> organized in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in November.'' <PERSON> Lallah </PERSON> said he also had received unofficial confirmation, and added: `` In October we are going to examine the third periodic -LRB- human rights -RRB- report of the <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION>, and it is possible that by then the decision will have been taken, or in process of being taken.'' A month ago, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> said it would accept <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jurisdiction in cases based on the Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and five other human rights treaties. The decision reversed a long policy of resisting outside judgment of its practices. The International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights guarantees the individual's right to life; freedom from torture, inhuman or degrading treatment; freedom from slavery or forced labor; freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention; freedom of movement; freedom of thought, conscience and peaceful assembly, and free association. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials praised last month's Soviet policy change but noted that only governments, not individuals, can file legal actions with the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, whose formal title is the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kooijmans </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special investigator on human rights, said at the time: `` It would be a real breakthrough for human rights if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would recognize the right of individuals'' to file complaints of rights abuses. Under the Optional Protocol, individual citizens can complain of rights abuses to the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, an international body of legal experts with the power to order compensation. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> ratified the protocol last year, joining 40 other nations that recognize it.
