 knew how to present himself, to negotiate, lobby, whatever,'' <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> also said the deal had a subcontract calling for <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> to receive $ 150,000 for future work should <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> be successful in winning the radar job. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> awarded the company the $ 24 million job in July 1987. Although details of <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>'s future work were not spelled out, <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said the arrangement was not a contingency fee, which is illegal under <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> procurement rules. Asked if he meant to conceal the $ 150,000 arrangement with <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said, `` Absolutely not. ... If you want to make something illegal, you should hide it, not put it out in public.'' <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said he had little contact with <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> between 1985 and late 1987. The defendant said he talked to the consultant for a total of about 15 minutes on the telephone and spent about an hour with him at a hotel near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in November 1987. At that meeting, <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> gave him two reports that might be useful to <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON> said he found only one contained valuable information while the other was `` just a bunch of garbage.'' <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> has testified that he indirectly paid money to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> left government in October 1983 after a 17-year career during which, he said, he accepted $ 50,000 in bribes. <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> already has pleaded guilty in the government's investigation of fraud and corruption in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </OR