<HEAD>Bell-Sponsored Survey Finds Support for Broader Bell Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of telephone users think the seven regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies should be allowed to enter the equipment manufacturing, long-distance and information services markets, according to a survey released Thursday by the telephone companies. In the random survey of 24,291 registered voters, 58 percent agreed that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year should consider lifting the restrictions placed on the Bell companies in the 1984 breakup of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In the <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T breakup, the regional phone companies were prohibited from entering the phone equipment research, development and manufacturing business and from providing their own long-distance and information services to local and national customers. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> reaffirmed those prohibitions last year, saying the Bell companies, if freed from their restraints, might engage in predatory pricing and cross-subsidization of services and discriminate against competitors wanting to use their phone lines. The court did allow the regional companies to provide `` gateway'' services through which users can call a single 800 number to gain access to a variety of services such as <ORGANIZATION> CompuServe </ORGANIZATION> and The Source databases. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Kennan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>, said his company's survey found that `` Americans want American companies freed to compete in providing telecommunications products and services. Consumers want as many choices as possible.'' According to <PERSON> Kennan </PERSON>: _ 74 percent of those surveyed said the seven <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> companies should be allowed to compete in the long-distance arena _ 78 percent thought those companies should be allowed to offer information services, which could include electronic banking, health monitoring, home security services and data bases _ 79 percent said the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies should be allowed to research, develop and manufacture telephone equipment _ 68 percent said the newspaper advertising business does not need to be protected from electronic yellow pages that the Bell companies could offer _ 74 percent said allowing the seven companies to compete in the telephone equipment market would strengthen <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness against overseas manufacturers of high technology equipment <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Linnen </PERSON> said those surveyed were n't told `` there is already stiff and growing competition for <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T'' in manufacturing equipment. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said in a recent speech in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the Bell companies, if allowed to begin manufacturing, might be inclined to team with overseas manufacturers to avoid huge development costs _ to the detriment of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> workers. <PERSON> Linnen </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN