<HEAD>More Records Fall As Heat Wave Keeps Grip On Region</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE temperatures for Los Angeles and
San Diego, other regional readings, heat damage to crops, ice sales booming.
Picks up 6th graf: Dr. George ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mercury hit 100 and kept going Thursday as <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> sweated out the third day of a record-breaking heat wave that sent thousands to the beach, increased power demand and withered strawberries. <LOCATION> Downtown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where the temperature peaked at 105 degrees Wednesday, registered 103 Thursday afternoon, breaking the date's record of 91 set in 1932 and tied in 1962. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>'s 98 made it the hottest April day on record. High pressure over the West squeezed warm air out of the interior toward the populous coast, beating back sea breezes and turning even the usually balmy beaches into a furnace for thousands who rushed there instead of work. `` It started off with 80 degrees at sunrise and now it's up to 98 in the shade,'' said <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> lifeguard <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> DeGregori </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> said power demand to keep up with air conditioning would beat the April record of 14,282 megawatts set Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>, the other major local supplier of electricity, projected an April record need for 4,700 megawatts by 4 p.m.. Other hot afternoon readings around <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> included 110 at <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, 108 at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Toro </LOCATION>, 107 at <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, 104 at <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, 102 at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, and 100 at <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Blythe </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> Much of the rest of the state shared the warmth, though not the triple digit readings. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> hit the upper 80s. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grower <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillebrecht </PERSON> watched three acres of strawberries in <LOCATION> Escondido </LOCATION> wither in a 105-degree <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION> wind. `` They're really melting in this heat,'' she said. `` You ca n't put enough water on the roots of the plant to keep it from losing moisture. Conversely, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> agricultural biologist <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said early warming of the soil would help summer vegetables just being planted. Since Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has sold about 30 tons a day to food and liquor stores, compared to the five or six tons normally delivered daily this time of year, said office manager <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gellert </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> health official, urged people to take precautions ranging from simply wearing hats to spending time in air-conditioned places such as shopping malls and supermarkets. The 61-degree ocean water might deter beachgoers from plunging in, but they should at least keep splashing themselves, <PERSON> Gellert </PERSON> said. `` People going to the beach and not going into the water are just exposing themselves to the sun. ... They may be better off remaining in the shade.'' <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> winds out of the interior began warming the region last weekend. By Tuesday, downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> reached 100 degrees, tying the all-time April record. Even normally cool <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> felt the heat Wednesday with a record high of 88, a full 8 degrees above the previous record that had stood since 1924. At 5 a.m. Thursday the mercury had dropped only to 74 in downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and 88 at <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peak </LOCATION> above Point Mugu in <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Even at 3 a.m. hundreds of people could be found parked along beaches seeking respite. <ORGANIZATION> SoCal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION>'s all-time record power use was last September when its 3.8 million central and southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> customers used 15,987 megawatts. The <ORGANIZATION> DWP </ORGANIZATION>'s all time record was 4,991 megawatts on Sept. 6, 1988. Tuesday's usage was 4,073 megawatts and Wednesday's was 4,541 megawatts. Even if high temperatures remain in the same range, power use increases over the span of a heat wave because lack of overnight cooling causes heat buildup in buildings, requiring more power to start up air conditioning each day.
