<FIRST>r a AM-Ravens-Tortoises     04-06 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ravens-Tortoises,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ravens to Die in Effort to Save Desert Tortoise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials plan to shoot and poison up to 1,500 ravens in the <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> in an effort to save the desert tortoise, which is a favorite meal of the predatory birds. Animal damage control officers with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> will kill ravens by injecting hard-boiled eggs with poison and placing the eggs on elevated platforms where the ravens will find and eat them. The ravens are killing young tortoises by the thousands and contributing to an alarming decline of tortoise populations in the desert, said biologists with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, the agency that developed the raven control program. <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> officials obtained a permit this week from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to kill the birds, the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernardino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. The birds are protected by the Migratory Bird Treaty Act. The permit represents the largest sanctioned killing of ravens in the Western states, said Agent <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> of the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> officials oppose the program and local <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> officials called it short-sighted and excessive. `` I'm a little annoyed at this,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> McKernan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernardino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` In general the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> is not doing its job throughout the desert on a variety of levels. ... It bothers me that they are now having to go to these extremes to eliminate or reduce a population.'' Roads, dumps, homes, power lines and sewage plants in the desert have helped boost raven populations 15-fold during the last two decades, <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> biologists said. The $ 50,000 raven control program, set to begin within the next two weeks, will last about four months and will be conducted in three areas, including the Desert Tortoise Natural Area preserve near <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Rado </PERSON>, a wildlife biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. The bait platforms, at least four feet high, will prevent other animals such as kit foxes and coyotes from eating the poisoned eggs, <PERSON> Rado </PERSON> said. Ravens die within 24 to 48 hours after eating the poison. Officials plan to shoot ravens and capture some with nets fired from cannons to supplement the poisoning program. Ravens favor tortoises seven years old and younger because their fingernail-thin shells are easily punctured with their beaks. As more and more young tortoises are eaten, fewer reach maturity and the adult reproductive population shrinks. In two studies, <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> biologists attributed 88 percent of tortoise deaths to ravens. But critics remain skeptical that ravens can cause so much damage.
