<HEAD>Police Break Up International Counterfeit Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials said Wednesday they broke up a major international counterfeit ring, confiscating $ 12 million in counterfeit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency and arresting a West German and an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> accomplice. The counterfeiters had operated since at least 1987 and their bogus money has turned up in several <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> cities and in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jochen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> prosecutors' office <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said investigators seized 235 pounds of counterfeit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> $ 100 bills with a total face value of $ 12 million. He said it was the largest seizure of counterfeit money in West German history. Printing machines and high-quality paper used by the counterfeiters were also confiscated in raids March 20 in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and the surrounding area, <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said. Two of the counterfeit ring's alleged organizers _ a 49-year-old Israeli and a 43-year-old West German businessman from the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> area _ were arrested, and an arrest warrant was issued for a third suspect, <PERSON> Schroers </PERSON> said. The spokesman refused to provide further information on any of the suspects. According to Schroers, West German authorities received their first clues about the counterfeiters in 1987 when they heard the ring wanted to circulate a large amount of their bogus money. `` We knew no more than that, until late summer 1988 when the first hundred or so hundred-dollar bills surfaced in various European cities, especially <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, but also in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' Schroers said. He said that American and Israeli authorities provided information about links between the counterfeitiers operating in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with another ring that was act