<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>``Drifting Away'' From Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The critics call it drift, and maybe they're right But there certainly is a prevailing current in the early course of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration _ and it leads away from some of the policies and positions bequeathed by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has made those moves carefully and quietly, item by item. He is putting his imprint on major programs, supplanting and in some cases undoing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> policies, transformations that have been taking place with scant notice and only a few complaints from conservatives. That's just fine with the White House. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his lieutenants need no trouble on the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> right, where the president never was a favorite. Most of the criticism has been coming from other directions, much of it from Democrats. Still, there are some ripples on the right. When Republican National Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> spoke at the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> the other night, one man complained that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has moved away from some favored conservative positions since the election. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a conservative,'' <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> replied. He said on two paramount issues, opposition to new taxes and a hard line against communism, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is solid and absolute. `` He remains hard core on both of those,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> chairman said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> denies that his administration is adrift. Challenging those who complain about the pace of administration action, he said in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> last month: `` In this kind of work, more is going on than meets the eye _ or makes the headlines. The proof will come when we look back from the year 2000.'' He's also countered by joking about the criticism. `` People say I'm indecisive,'' he said last week. Presidential pause. `` I do n't know about that. `` Some started saying that the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> did n't have an agenda,'' said Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` We have an agenda. It's just that when <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> left, he took it with him. Jokes aside, if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> came back, he may not recognize some of that agenda. White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, who served both men, says the Reagan-to-Bush revisions are in approach, not in goals. He says they differ at the margin, not on the basics. From the outset, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he envisioned no radical change in course from the administration he served as vice president. Nevertheless, some <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> positions have been retired since he did. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s agreement with the Democrats on aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels is a prime example. The administration has agreed to seek only non-military aid, only through next February and subject to congressional committee veto. Since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has rejected military aid, the net result is similar to what <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> got. But administration policy now is to seek diplomatic answers in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, rather than look to military ones. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who negotiated the deal with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, acknowledged the failure of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> policy. `` We all have to admit that the policy failed to some extent because we were not united,'' he said. `` We had an executive branch going in one direction and a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> going in the other.'' On the domestic agenda, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has embraced a compromise version of a bill _ which <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> pocket vetoed _ to protect federal employees who blow the whistle on waste, abuse and mismanagement. The compromise might have satisfied <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>; he never said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposed any increase in the $ 3.35 hourly minimum wage. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has endorsed an increase, tied to a lower-than-minimum training wage for new workers. Congressional Democrats want a higher minimum and a more restricted training wage. That's still in dispute and the administration has talked of a veto unless there is a satisfactory compromise. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also has moved away from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> position on the question of gun controls, which also was his own _ a flat no. The administration on Wednesday widened its import ban on foreign-made assault rifles, and an official said it is considering a proposal that gun buyers register such weapons. Even those modest moves drew the standard protests from the gun lobby, despite the growing sense of crisis over drug-related violence in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities and the murder of five children in a <LOCATION> Stockton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, schoolyard. <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> told his conservative audience that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remains opposed to gun control despite the moves against assault rifles, on which he said there is growing public sentiment in favor of limits. `` If the conservative position is pro-assault rifle, you'd better get out and start moving around'' to hear the public outcry, <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said
</TEXT>
