ker loadings at the port. Cclaimed to have no problem with crude supplies to its major <LOCATION> Wesst </LOCATION> refineries, in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> areas. ` <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> has n't had to limit refinery activity at all,'' <PERSON> Libbey </PERSON>. `` I gather from what I hear that the independents -LRB- smaller oil companies -RRB- are squeezed more tightly than we a they do n't have the resources we have and room to maneuver.'' <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> said it would not be able to provide infomation on whether it has a similar gasoline dist effect until sometime today, and information from other major il companies was n't immediately available. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s deliveries to retail gasoline stations served directly are not affected by the cap because those stations ca n't keep much gasoline in storage, <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said He did not know how much of <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s gasoline in Western states goes as opposed to retailers. Once operations are returned to normal in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, gasoline prices will start dropping, but not by much, he said. Most of the increases consumers have seen since the New Year are the result of a decision last fall by the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations to limit production. And, he added, the popular summer driving season is approaching, meaning demand will stay high and keep prices up.
