<HEAD>Davis Says He Would Not Bust Up Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 3.50 to a record-high $ 87.25 a share after oil mogul <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said his $ 2.62 billion proposal to buy the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> would not require selling the carrier's main assets. `` We do not intend to ` bust up' the company, and our planned financing will not necessitate the sale of any of the company's strategic assets,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said in a letter he sent to <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors Tuesday and released to the media Wednesday More than 2.5 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> stock changed hands Wednesday. The Los Angeles-based billionaire, whose holdings include real estate and entertainment properties, owns about 3 percent of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s 29.1 million shares and offered to pay $ 90 a share for <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> stock in a letter last week to company directors `` With the equity we are prepared to commit and the anticipated structure of the balance of the financing, the company's projected cash flow is adequate to service the debt involved,'' the second letter said. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said in the letter that his group is `` prepared to increase the price of our offer in the context of a negotiated transaction.'' A spokesman for the nation's fourth-largest air carrier, based in suburban <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, confirmed receipt of the letter, but said the company would not comment. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothmeier </PERSON> has said the directors will review the offer, but he has not said when. The airline has said it intends to remain independent. State officials have rallied behind the carrier, introducing legislation intended to thwart a hostile takeover. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>., met with <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> representatives Wednesday and spoke later by telephone with <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> Afterward, they told reporters they still opposed the billionaire's offer. <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aviation subcommittee, said they remained concerned that <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> would have to sell parts of the airline to finance the deal. They said that might result in layoffs and in Northwest moving its service hub from Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION> 143, said he remains `` suspicious'' of <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' offer because <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> has not provided specifics about how he would finance it. `` I believe he has a history of buying and selling companies,'' said <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, who heads the union representing two-thirds of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s 35,000 employees. `` He has ownership for a period of time and then he sells it off.'' <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivard </PERSON>, a financial analyst for Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Dain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the increase in <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price Wednesday suggests confidence on the part of investors that a higher bid is on its way. `` It could come from <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION>, it could come from <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, it could come from somewhere else,'' <PERSON> Rivard </PERSON> said. Before <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> made his offer, the company disclosed a separate group of investors was interested in buying <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>. The identity of that group, which said it owns 4.9 percent of the stock, has not been disclosed. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> repeated in his letter an earlier statement that he intends to expand the airline's domestic and international routes and keep the headquarters in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. He also said his plans call for `` no employee layoffs, work-force reductions or alterations in seniority schedules.'' The letter said <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> management would be retained, but also said, `` we intend to effect only those management changes required to improve <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s performance.'' Analysts have said a takeover could impair <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s fleet modernization plans because <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> would have to sell assets and cuts operating costs to service takeover debt. But <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said in his letter that the acquisition plan `` in no way calls for the reduction of the company's present capital investment program.'' Northwest has discussed profit-sharing and stock ownership plans with its unions for more than a year. Analysts have said an employee stock ownership plan could help the carrier defend itself against a takeover by putting more stock in friendly hands.
