<HEAD>Milken Asks Supreme Court To Consider Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 2-3, Meanwhile, unnamed ... disclosure obligations,
to UPDATE with published reports of negotiations with Drexel client. Picks
up 2nd graf pvs, The petition ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> have asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to consider removing the judge in charge of the settlement of insider trading charges against the deposed bond financier and his former employer, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, unnamed sources quoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> today said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, chief investment officer of <ORGANIZATION> Solomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, was negotiating with prosecutors to cooperate in the government's case against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>. He would be the first <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> client to testify against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> should he become a witness. The investigation is believed to focus on allegations of `` parking'' of junk bonds and stocks by <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>'s company, according to the Journal. When parking occurs securities are bought with the understanding that they'll be sold back to the original owner, usually at a prearranged time and price. The process is intended to hide their true ownership to avoid tax or disclosure obligations. The petition filed Wednesday asks the court to hear their appeal of a lower court decision allowing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> to preside over the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> Lawyers for <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, who also was named in the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> suit filed last September, claim <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> should be disqualified because his wife stands to make $ 30 million from a leveraged buyout <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> helped finance. They allege the transaction represents a conflict of interest for <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, who must approve any final settlement between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> were charged last week with a range of criminal securities law violations in a 98-count racketeering and fraud indictment that capped a two-year government investigation. A bond hearing on the charges, in which the government is seeking $ 1.8 billion in penalties, is set for Friday. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> headed <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s California-based high-yield junk bond division and made a reported $ 550 million in 1987 before stepping down after the indictment to prepare his defense. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> petition came after the 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in late February refused to rehear a bid to remove <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> from the case. But that court did grant a stay against <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> issuing any rulings. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> settlement is a crucial precondition to resolving criminal securities fraud charges against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. The firm in December agreed to pay $ 650 million and plead guilty to six felonies to settle the criminal charges with the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office. Negotiations between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> hit a roadblock last month over the federal government's demand to fire <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> before the pact was reached. That condition, though, may be be moot since <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has left the firm. A majority of the 12-member appeals court rejected a bid to allow the full panel to hear the case against <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>. But in a dissent, four judges said the the case would continue under `` a cloud'' if <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> were allowed to preside. Both a district court judge and a three-member appeals court panel also rejected dismissing <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>. `` We're faced with a situation where we are in a litigation with a potentially adversarial party, namely <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, where that party was responsible for $ 30 million going to the wife of the judge,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, attorney for <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>. `` We think that is a perception that merits the judge stepping aside,'' he said. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s lawyers also are challenging the criminal fraud settlement in federal court, saying it violates his rights by forcing the firm to fire him and withhold his 1988 pay of more than $ 100 million.
