<HEAD>USAir, Teamsters To Begin Contract Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> has told the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> it would begin negotiating with the union on a contract for some 4,000 fleet service workers in 101 cities, according to a newspaper report. But the airline has n't dropped its opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>, which narrowly won an election last December to expand its representation of fleet services workers from 1,900 in four cities to the entire <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> system, today's <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Gazette </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> told a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, that it would appeal last Friday's dismissal of a lawsuit it filed challenging the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to certify the union as representing the 4,000 workers. The nation's seventh-largest airline said through spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> that it would bargain in good faith as it pursues the suit, which accuses the board of failing to investigate alleged election improprieties. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Genoese </PERSON>, director of the Teamster's airline division, called the company's decision to bargain for all 4,000 baggage handlers, air freight handlers and catering employees a victory. `` For them to come out and say they would recognize 101 cities, they were eating crow,'' he told a packed membership meeting Wednesday at a motel near the Greater <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Prior to the December election, which the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> won by only a four-vote margin, the union had represented 1,900 workers at airports in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, N.Y. The election gave the union the right to extend its representation to 900 former employees of <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> who lost their Teamster affiliation when the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> carrier was merged into <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> last year, and to another 1,200 previously unorganized workers at smaller <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> stations. The Teamsters, currently working under a contract that has been open for amendment since July 1987, also are asking a federal court to order <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> to grant the union access to work sites and employee records and to set up a grievance procedure for those not previously represented, Genoese said. The union is seeking elimination of a two-tier wage system and retroactive pay increases of 10 percent annually. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> has offered 3 percent wage hikes and some benefit improvements, according to the union, but wants to maintain the lower rate scale for workers hired after May 1985.
