<HEAD>Pasta to Get Special Trademark</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Traditional Italian pasta will get a special government quality-control mark under a measure aimed at helping consumers distinguish it from cheaper imported mixed-wheat pasta, news reports said Thursday. According to the measure, approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> and expected to take effect this year, foreign pasta-makers will have to list their ingredients on packages they want to sell in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Even diners in restaurants will have to be notified of the type of pasta they are eating, according to the new law. Traditional Italian pasta, made from durum wheat, stays firm when cooked, an important quality for those who like it `` al dente.'' In July, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> overturned an Italian law that barred the sale of pasta not made entirely with durum wheat. The Italian pasta industry has been concerned that consumers will be tempted to turn to the less firm mixed-wheat pasta, which costs up to 30 percent less than durum pasta and is produced in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>.
