<HEAD>Maxwell Reports Higher 1988 Pretax Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC, the British conglomerate that acquired <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> last year for $ 2.6 billion, on Thursday reported its 1988 pretax profits rose 8.7 percent In the year ended Dec. 31, pretax profit rose to 180.4 million pounds, or $ 306.7 million, from 166 million pounds, or $ 282.2 million a year earlier, the company said. Profit after taxes and minority interest rose 2.8 percent to $ 230.5 million, from $ 224.06 million the year before, the company said. Earnings fell to 37.5 cents a share from 45.3 cents, a drop of 20.8 percent, because of a 70 percent expansion in share capital from a rights issue last July. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> said its sales rose 27.6 percent to $ 1.90 billion, from $ 1.5 billion a year earlier. Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> said last year `` saw the achievement of our grand strategy of transforming within a few years a practically bankrupt printing company into one of the big 10 global communications and information corporations.'' In addtion to the November takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> reached agreement in October with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> publisher <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> to buy the <ORGANIZATION> Official </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Guide for $ 750 million.
