<SECOND>BC-Mustang Anniversary, Adv 09,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Original Pony Car Celebrates 25th Birthday; Still Going Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was the car cool Baby Boomers grooved on. The Mustang, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s breakthrough into lightweight, affordable sports cars, turns 25 this month with an immortalized place in auto history, making its mark the same way the Beatles reshaped rock' n'roll. Teen-agers dreamed of cruising drive-ins in their new <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> which, like the dreamers themselves, grow older by the year. Some original Mustang drivers say they do n't feel a day older than when they slid behind the wheel for the first time. `` It felt great,'' <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> remembered about the day 25 years ago when he drove the first Mustang ever made at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, assembly plant, where 52 of the cars an hour still roll off the line. <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON> <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> of East Detroit got into the Mustang love affair late. But she got her driver's license late, too. She bought a used'68 Mustang when she got her license in 1973 at age 46. `` It makes you feel young,'' she said at a suburban <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Jeep-Eagle dealership where she and her husband were shopping for a new car. They pulled up in a'66 light blue and white Mustang _ a car she says she wo n't trade. The nation is dotted with <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> clubs and <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON> collectors. About 75 percent of the members in the <ORGANIZATION> Performance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are Mustang owners, said club chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Crites </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Mustang lovers praise what they call the simplicity of the early model, promoting an exuberance and free spirit that captivated young consumers and made <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s rivals rethink and redesign their own sporty models. The original Mustang, unveiled when <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> was president of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, had a base a price of $ 2,368 and featured a 170-cubic-inch, six-cylinder engine. `` It could be fixed by a general novice person in the back yard,'' in the early years, <PERSON> Crites </PERSON> said. `` Simplicity has gone out with cheap gas.'' <PERSON> Crites </PERSON> said he's owned about 15 <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> over the years, and has three in his collection of 25 cars. His favorite Mustang is the 1969 <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shelby </ORGANIZATION> GT 500. Like other Mustang buyers, Crites is proud of how he found his pride and joy. `` In 1970, I went in -LRB- to a dealership -RRB- to buy a truck,'' he said. `` I saw the Mustang sitting there for $ 3,700. I went back two weeks later and they dropped the price by about $ 500.'' Crites drove it away that day. He was one of hundreds of thousands who bought <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> during the early years. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> formally introduced the car on April 17, 1964, about five weeks after <PERSON> Mustang </PERSON>'s Job 1 rolled out of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> plant Some purists call the first editions 1964 -LCB- models. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> calls them' 65s The first-year sales projection of 100,000 cars was passed in four months. Sales increased to its best year in 1966, when 549,400 Mustangs were driven off <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> dealership lots. The second generation of <PERSON> Mustangs </PERSON>, called the Mustang II, was introduced for the 1974 model year. It was a smaller than the'73, reflecting the need for better fuel efficiency during the oil crunch of the mid-1970s. Mustang sales bottomed out in 1983 at about 117,000 cars, raising predictions that the car, like an aging television sit-com, had finally run out of gas. But last year, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 170,100 <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION>. The 1989 Mustang, which has a four-cylinder engine, has a base price $ 9,450. An optional beefed-up 5.0-liter engine capable of 223 horsepower compared with 90 horsepower in the basic engine, is a popular seller. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has said it plans to commemorate the Mustang birthday this April 17 with a low-key event at its <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> headquarters but does n't plan a special edition of the car and is leaving the hoopla to others. A caravan of 37 <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> owned by Europeans is tooling around the country on what's been billed as the `` American Pony Drive.'' The caravan started March 24 in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and winds up May 9 in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. But whether in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or overseas, <ORGANIZATION> Mustang </ORGANIZATION>'s design has been what's attracted buyers. `` I just like the way it looks,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> said. `` It's sporty looking. End Advance for Sunday, April 9
