<HEAD>Sale Of First Mustang A Mistake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Mustang Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sale of the first Mustang off the assembly line was a mistake. It had nothing to do with the car. It was the salesman doing his job too well, according to <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, a corporate airline pilot now based in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. `` They should have known better, I guess,'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> was 32 when he was in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, driving by <ORGANIZATION> Parsons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> on April 14, 1964. There, on a pedestal, was a white Mustang convertible, with a black interior. `` I went in and said I want to buy it,'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> recalled, not knowing that the car was in the eastern <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> province as part of a promotional tour a few days before the Mustang officially was introduced. `` I guess the salesman did n't realize he should n't sell it,'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said. `` I wrote him out a check and drove the car off.'' A few days later, the dealer called <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> asking him to return the car. `` I said ` No way.' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> called and they could n't get the car back either,'' he said. `` I was driving that thing around for about six months -LRB- in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> -RRB- before I ever saw another,'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said. `` It felt great. The car was stopping traffic on the streets. People would come over and say, ` What in heaven's name is that?''' In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> were no strangers on the road. The car got off to one of the hottest starts in automotive history, topping its annual projection of 100,000 sales in the first four months. The appearance of the car was the thing that caught the eye of <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> and hundreds of thousands of other buyers in the early days. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> kept the original Mustang for two years. `` After a couple of years, they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- came up with a gimmick and said, ` How about trading the first car in for the millionth?' I was stupid enough to do it.'' The original Mustang, serial number 55F08F100001, is on display now at the <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, unrelated to automobile designer <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of the 1940s, said he had no problem with the original Mustang during the two years he owned the car During that time, he put 10,000 miles on it, about half of the usual mileage. Open road is scarce on <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>. `` What I'm sorry of in hindsight is getting rid of the first one,'' he said. `` If I had any brains, I would have put it up on blocks and let it appreciate.'' End adv for Sunday, April 9
