 Most futures prices for soybeans and corn were higher while most wheat prices were lower at the close Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was a choppy market, very quiet,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON>, CBOT floor operations manager for <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's not an exciting time down here.'' Corn prices were supported by the announcement that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought an additional 200,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, said research director <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> LIT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Reduced domestic demand and increasing supplies from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> weighed on May soybeans, which were off a penny at the close, <PERSON> Zusel </PERSON> said. Wheat was lower on the lack of fresh export news, analysts said. At the close, wheat was unchanged to 6 -RCB- cents lower, with the contract for delivery in May at $ 3.97 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 1 cent higher, with May at $ 2.64 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3 cents higher, with May at $ 1.86 a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent lower to 4 cents higher, with May at $ 7.14 a bushel.
