<HEAD>Joint-Venture Steel Plant Dedicated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sprawling steel plant that has been modernized at a cost of $ 400 million for use in a joint venture by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company and its South Korean partner was dedicated Thursday while protesters outside burned <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> flags. The 80-year-old factory was renovated as part of a pact between <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and giant <ORGANIZATION> Pohang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and now has an annual capacity of 1.4 million tons of finished steel products, mainly material for tin cans, steel-framed furniture and appliances. The <ORGANIZATION> USS-POSCO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> plant is part of a 500-acre complex in this community about 50 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Former President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, who spoke at the dedication and flipped the switch to put the gleaming machines and computers to work, said joint ventures are an inevitable trend in business and politics. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> commended officials of both companies for `` the vision and dedication to see the rebirth of the steel industry in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.'' He recalled that experts had predicted the end of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry, but `` fortunately, the pessimists were wrong.'' The plant, which began operation in 1909 and has n't been in full production for almost 20 years, was the scene of a protest by about 500 people, including members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Longshoremen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warehousemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> They were objecting to the use of non-union labor to handle the renovation. `` We want people to know how it affects not just the nation, but the local community,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Belleci </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> ILWU </ORGANIZATION> member. Plant president <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roskovensky </PERSON>, who said the plant does employ union labor, said the protest stemmed from an ongoing disagreement over the hiring of non-union contractors after a union bid came in far over the cost of non-union labor. Under terms of a 1986 agreement, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> and Pohang each owns half the plant and invested $ 90 million in its rejuvenation. The pact is similar to the agreement between <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> which created <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The balance of the money invested _ $ 220 million _ came from bank financing. Pohang's investment is the largest ever by a South Korean company in the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. The plant will be a boon to the local economy, employing some 1,200 people and paying them a total of about $ 46 million annually. The venture already has paid some $ 12 million in state sales taxes. Flanking the podium as <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spoke was a poster showing three workers and the slogan, `` We're a whole new breed of steel-maker.'' Asked whether the plant posed a threat to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> board chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said it was n't going to cause `` one iota'' of trouble. `` This is a solution ... to keep an American steel presence on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>,'' he said. Gen. <PERSON> Tae-Joon </PERSON> <PERSON> Park </PERSON>, chairman of Pohang, lauded those who put the deal together despite `` all sorts of odds and difficulties.''
