are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Assets of the nation's 465 money market mutual funds rose by $ 1.16 billion in the latest week to a new all-time high of $ 301.2 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The increase from the previous record of $ 300.04 billion set last week marked the 13th straight weekly all-time high for the funds' assets and reflected the growing attraction of such investments because of rising interest rates. The previous record originally was reported as $ 299.62 billion but the Washington-based mutual fund trade group revised it upward. The <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said that in the week ended Wednesday, assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $ 573.3 million to $ 98.62 billion, assets of 94 broker-dealer funds increased $ 462.4 million to $ 129.39 billion, and assets of 140 institutional funds rose $ 128.2 million to $ 73.18 billion. The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in the week ended Tuesday to 9.08 percent from 9.04 percent the previous week, said <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s Money Fund Report, a trade journal based in <LOCATION> Holliston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The 30-day average yield rose to 8.97 from 8.89 percent, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds remained unchanged at 31 days, <PERSON> Donoghue </PERSON>'s said. The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to 6.61 percent as of Wednesday from 6.56 percent a week earlier. The <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW accounts, were unchanged at 5.14 percent. Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.27 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 9.17 the previous week. Yields were 9.45 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.38 percent; 9.31 percent on 2 -LCB- - year CDs, up from 9.29 percent; and 9.21 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 9.20 percent
