<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Six months after <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> won a rare hostile bid to acquire rival <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the banking industry may see another big takeover war. But although the unsolicited $ 2.4 billion buyout proposal by giant <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is in some ways similar to the 13-month battle between <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, the latest deal has some key differences. It's bigger, could be more likely to generate opposition from state and federal regulators and involves two institutions considered strong financial performers. `` I guess I'd have to say it pretty much stops and ends with the fact that both were unsolicited offers,'' said <PERSON> Rodgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a merger specialist with the law firm <ORGANIZATION> Sullivan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Cromwell </PERSON> who is working for Atlanta-based Citizens. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.4 billion hostile takeover battle for <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> was n't the first hostile bank deal, but it was the largest of its kind to succeed in a banking industry that traditionally had relied mainly on friendly deals. `` I think the Irving-Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> deal definitely broke the ice,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> attorney specializing in bank mergers, said Thursday. `` A lot of people felt that deal was an aberration. But now it's happening again, which is noteworthy.'' Citizens' board of directors on Monday rejected the stock-swap merger proposal by <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, N.C.-based <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> as inadequate. Experts see some similarities between the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> deal and the <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> proposal, but there also are plenty of differences. The combination of the two would result in a bank with assets of around $ 75 billion, placing it firmly in the top 10 among the nation's bank holding companies. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> grew to about $ 50 billion in assets after the Irving acquisition. Also, `` <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> was a mediocre performer that did n't live up to its potential, whereas Citizens has been a strong performer that is living up to its potential,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDermott </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Keefe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bruyette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> is offering 1.075 of its shares for each of Citizens' stock, or around $ 44 a share The company has hinted it might be willing to raise its bid by around $ 5 a share if Citizens agrees to negotiations. But Citizens' management and many analysts maintain that even that's too low. <ORGANIZATION> NBNC </ORGANIZATION> stock closed unchanged at $ 34.25 a share Thursday. Citizens fdeclined 25 cents to $ 35 a share. Citizens' main criticism of the offer is that the value of <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s stock may have been inflated after <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> took over the management of the banks of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> RepublicBank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> last year with the government's financial assistance. That bank is now called <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Federal Reserve may look unfavorably upon the acquisition by <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> of another bank given the fact that they recently received federal assistance to acquire First RepublicBank,'' <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> _ who represented <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> in its fight for <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> _ said Thursday that no negotiations have been held and none are planned with <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>. He said the company has not been talking to any other potential suitor. `` It's quite clear Citizens wants to remain independent,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. After Citizens' board rejected <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s offer it amended the company's bylaws to make a takeover more difficult, applying provisions <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s anti-takeover law. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> relied on a similar <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law, but lost several key court challenges to the statute. Also unlike the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-Irving </ORGANIZATION> battle, the <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> proposal reaches across state lines. `` It's likely that there will be a lot more politics involved in this battle ... -LRB- because -RRB- it's likely it would result in the reduction of jobs,'' said <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON>. `` <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> has a very strong track record of cutting costs and reducing staff.'' While <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal calls for continuation of Citizens and Southern's management and independent operations, banking experts said they were doubtful <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> would be a hands-off partner. `` First RepublicBank is a prime example. After they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- took that over they changed the name,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Biggar </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>.
