<HEAD>New Pricing Policy Propels Sears' Sales Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Retail Sales Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Retailing giant <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Thursday reported robust sales growth for the first month of its new low-pricing policy but analysts said it will take many months to judge whether <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' determination to beat competitors is paying <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> said its sales rose 11.9 percent in the five weeks ended April 1 to $ 2.97 billion from $ 2.66 billion in the corresponding period a year earlier. Sales at <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> stores open for at least a year increased a solid 9.6 percent during the five weeks. The industry considers these same-store sales a better measure of a retailer's performance than totals that includes the take at newly opened stores. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bozic </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said the March volume turned out even better than the company had hoped. `` Clearly, everyday low prices are well-understood and popular with the public and we are pleased with the response to our strategy,'' <PERSON> Bozic </PERSON> said. The launch of its `` everyday low price'' program, which was promoted with an aggressive advertising campaign estimated by outsiders to have cost about $ 110 million, definitely brought more customers into <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> stores. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronning </PERSON>, a retail specialist with <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> Bros.. <PERSON> Harriman </PERSON>, said the sales growth was a `` reflection of people experimenting to see what <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> everyday low pricing is like. `` It shows people are going into the stores to find out what's happening,'' he said One of the strongest points to make about <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' latest same-store sales were that they rose 15.4 percent after adjustment for the loss of 2 -LCB- selling days due to Easter and the closing of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' more than 800 stores nationwide for marking down prices in preparation for the policy switch, <PERSON> Ronning </PERSON> said. The markdowns were part of a broad effort by <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> to hoist its sagging merchandise operation. The retailer also is adding national brands to its mostly private-label lineup and cutting costs to recapture lost market share. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, which maintained its ranking as the country's biggest retailer with 1988 revenue of $ 30.3 billion, has watched its market share shrink this decade as go-go discounters such as <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and specialty merchants have developed significant followings among shoppers. Industry analysts said the test will be whether <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> manages to maintain the sales momentum, especially after the fan-fare over the changes adopted by the 102-year-old retailer dies down. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' advertising already has returned to a more normal level <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sack </PERSON>, a retail analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> definitely enjoyed a far better month than many of the other retailers that reported results on Thursday. No. 2 retailer <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, described its sales as `` disappointing'' and blamed the weather, in part Analysts said some of the weakness in sales at K mart and other chain stores may have been the result of all the hoopla generated by <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> policy shift but it is difficult to quantify precisely how much sales revenue might have been taken away by <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>. `` It will really take the better part of a year to determine whether their new policy is really taking hold,'' <PERSON> Sack </PERSON> said. Analysts are awaiting an indication if <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' bottom line is benefiting from the reduced prices. A <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said the company has been mum about predicting any impact on its earnings.
