<HEAD>Energy Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Meanwhile, the ... to delete cents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures were mostly lower in moderate trading Thursday, led by falling gasoline prices as oil shipments in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> returned to normal. Unleaded gasoline had risen more than 13 cents since the giant spill off the Alaskan coast on March 24. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, unleaded gasoline for May delivery dropped 1.88 cents to 64.55 cents a gallon from 66.43 a gallon on Wednesday. Other contract months were mixed. The May contract for heating oil fell .41 cent to 51.22 cents from 51.63 cents in the previous session, while other contracts also declined. Meanwhile, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, settled down 19 cents at $ 19.80 a barrel. Analysts said gasoline prices were in for a technical correction after soaring in the week following the oil spill and the closure of the port of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>. `` Prices reflected mostly a technical change rather than anything fundamental,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Redoglio </PERSON>, energy broker with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said oil shipments from the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> port exceeded 1.3 million barrels on Thursday while 2 million barrels are normally shipped.
