<HEAD>Dollar Opened Slightly Lower, Stocks Gain Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar opened marginally lower againt the Japanese yen Friday while share prices rebounded moderately in morning trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar, which gained 0.78 yen Thursday, opened at 132.10 yen, down 0.05 yen from the previous day's close. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 365.01-point loser Thursday, gained 55.12 points, or 0.17 percent, during the first 15 minutes of trading Friday. Currency dealers said they expected quiet trading throughout the day ahead of the release of unemployment figures in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, scheduled for Friday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` In a general trend, the dollar remains bullish mainly because of the gap in interest rates between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' said a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The unstable political situation in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is also expected to promote the yen's decline for some time.'' Securities dealers said investors are trying to determine the direction of the market, after the Nikkei index's sharp drop Thursday following a nearly 1,800-point gain from the start of this week.
