they were glad to see him go. `` It looks like mighty <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> has struck out,'' laughed <PERSON> Sal </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallavollita </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilot for 26 years. `` We are ready to accept concessions _ if that's what the new management wants, I'll go along with it. Ramp service worker <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorie </PERSON> said the price of the 34-day walkout was expensive, both to the employees and the airline itself. `` We know the airline has been hurt _ how much, we'll have to find out,'' <PERSON> Lorie </PERSON> said. `` We just have to go out there with the best possible mentality.'' Not everyone was ecstatic about the sale, with some saying they want to see the fine print. `` I've seen so much deception that I'm not going to pick up my tools until I've seen -LRB- the contract -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>, a maintenance worker for 23 years. But he said he was willing to make concessions to <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>. Most echoed the sentiments of <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Orent </PERSON>, a mechanic who rocked her little girl in a stroller as she listened to the excited chatter at the union hall. `` Even if we do n't all go back to work, for those who do, it's the greatest,'' she said `` <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s gone, he's gone back to wherever he came from, and we do n't want to see him again.''
